3876a3ca-4691-45e3-a146-84592b79b099	Stripe	Stripe builds economic infrastructure for the internet, providing APIs and tools for online payment processing and commerce.	Stripe is a financial infrastructure platform that enables businesses of all sizes to accept payments, manage revenue, and accelerate business growth online. Founded in 2010 by Irish brothers Patrick and John Collison, the company provides a suite of APIs and tools that allow developers to integrate payment processing into websites and mobile applications with minimal effort. Stripe handles billions of dollars in transactions annually for millions of businesses worldwide, from startups to Fortune 500 companies like Amazon, Google, and Shopify.\n\nBeyond core payment processing, Stripe has expanded into a comprehensive financial platform offering products including Stripe Connect (marketplace payments), Stripe Atlas (business incorporation), Stripe Capital (business lending), Stripe Treasury (banking-as-a-service), Stripe Billing (subscription management), Stripe Radar (fraud prevention), Stripe Tax (automated tax compliance), Stripe Issuing (card creation), and Stripe Climate (carbon removal). The company has become one of the most valuable private technology companies in the world.\n\nStripe's significance lies in its role as critical infrastructure powering the digital economy. By dramatically simplifying the complexity of online payments and financial services, Stripe has lowered barriers to entry for internet businesses globally. The company operates in over 45 countries and supports hundreds of payment methods, positioning itself as the default payments backbone for the modern internet economy.	Fintech	API / Platform	Growth	Stripe has raised approximately $9.4 billion in total funding across multiple rounds. Key rounds include: Seed round in 2010-2011 from Y Combinator, Peter Thiel, and Elon Musk; Series A (~$18M, 2012) led by Sequoia Capital; Series B ($80M, 2014) led by Founders Fund; Series C ($150M, 2016, ~$9B valuation) with General Catalyst, CapitalG; Series D ($245M, 2018, $20B valuation) with Tiger Global; Series E ($250M, 2019, $35B valuation) with Andreessen Horowitz, General Catalyst, Sequoia; Series G ($600M, 2020, $36B valuation); Series H ($600M, March 2021, $95B valuation) with Sequoia, Fidelity, Andreessen Horowitz, Baillie Gifford, and others; Series I ($6.5B, March 2023, $50B valuation) with Andreessen Horowitz, Baillie Gifford, Founders Fund, General Catalyst, Goldman Sachs, Temasek, and others. By 2024-2025, the company's secondary market valuation rose significantly, reportedly reaching $91.5 billion or higher in secondary share sales in early 2025. Notable investors include Sequoia Capital, Andreessen Horowitz, General Catalyst, Tiger Global, Founders Fund, Fidelity, Baillie Gifford, CapitalG (Alphabet), Goldman Sachs, Temasek, and GIC.	1. **Adyen** - Netherlands-based public company offering end-to-end payment processing for large enterprises; differentiates with a single-platform approach but Stripe is more developer-friendly and startup-oriented. 2. **PayPal / Braintree** - PayPal's Braintree competes directly in developer payment APIs; Stripe differentiates with superior developer experience, broader product suite, and faster innovation. 3. **Square (Block)** - Focuses more on in-person/SMB payments with growing online presence; Stripe differentiates by focusing primarily on internet-native businesses and providing more extensive APIs. 4. **Checkout.com** - UK-based payment processor competing for enterprise clients; Stripe differentiates with its broader ecosystem of financial products beyond payments. 5. **Worldpay / FIS** - Legacy payment processors serving large enterprises; Stripe differentiates with modern API-first architecture, developer tools, and agility in product development.		discovered	{Payments,"Developer Tools","Financial Infrastructure",B2B,"API Platform"}	\N	2026-03-04 12:08:32.972403	\N	\N	\N	\N	1e9bf641-c93c-46