d4723d25-5491-4921-930c-bc9e31668b16	3d49234e-2717-4407-ac7c-7f062f22bc96	1e9bf641-c93c-4629-906a-f50db9050164	Fireplace — Deep Research Report	\n\nI'll conduct extensive research on Fireplace across multiple angles. Let me start with several parallel searches.Good, I have solid baseline information. Now let me search for competitive landscape, Socket Protocol partnership, Frachtis and White Star Capital details, and market sizing.Now let me search for more specific details on Sumer Malhotra's background, prediction market total addressable market, and White Star Capital.Let me now search for more details on TradeFox and Verso (the most directly comparable competitors), and Kalshi's revenue numbers to frame the market opportunity.Now I have comprehensive data. Let me compile the full research report.\n\n# Fireplace — Deep Research Report\n\n---\n\n## Executive Summary\n\n**What it is:** Fireplace is a Hong Kong-based pre-seed startup building a professional trading terminal for prediction markets — often described as "the Bloomberg Terminal for prediction markets." The platform offers a unified terminal that aggregates markets, liquidity, and execution across prediction market venues, delivering real-time data, institution-grade execution, advanced charting, wallet, whale, and insider tracking, and discovery. Wallet technology and automations are powered by its in-house Enclave Money infrastructure. The platform integrates with venues including Polymarket and Kalshi and uses chain abstraction technology via Socket Protocol.\n\n**Why it matters / core thesis:** Prediction markets are experiencing explosive growth — total notional trading volume reached over $44 billion in 2025, with Polymarket and Kalshi generating around 85%–90% of the total volume. According to The Block's "2026 Digital Assets Outlook Report," Polymarket and Kalshi generated a combined volume of more than $37 billion in 2025, and the two platforms raised an estimated $3.6 billion in equity investment. Yet the tooling layer remains nascent — traders lack cross-venue aggregation, smart order routing, and institutional-grade analytics. Fireplace is positioning itself as the infrastructure aggregation layer atop rapidly scaling underlying platforms, analogous to how Bloomberg Terminal sits above financial exchanges. If venues continue to fragment across chains and jurisdictions, aggregation becomes essential; if liquidity deepens, professional tools gain leverage; if ETFs launch and institutional hedging grows, demand for execution quality compounds.\n\n**Key numbers and upcoming catalysts:**\n- In its first five months, Fireplace reports more than 30,000 traders on its waitlist, over 10,000 organic followers on X, an official Polymarket badge, and a public launch on January 27, 2026.\n- $1.5M pre-seed raised in February 2026, led by Frachtis, with participation from White Star Capital, plus syndicate rounds on Legion and Echo.\n- Key catalysts: Cross-venue smart order routing rollout, deeper Kalshi integration, potential prediction market ETF approvals, and continued fragmentation driving aggregator demand.\n\n---\n\n## Product Overview\n\n### Core Product Mechanics\nFireplace offers a unified terminal that aggregates markets, liquidity, and execution across prediction market venues, delivering real-time data, advanced charting, wallet/whale/insider tracking, and discovery. Wallet technology and automations are powered by in-house Enclave Money infrastructure. As prediction markets fragment across platforms and chains, Fireplace supports cross-venue aggregation with smart order routing — rather than forcing traders to manually compare prices and liquidity across venues, Fireplace intelligently routes orders when the same market exists in multiple places.\n\nThe platform uses chain abstraction technology in collaboration with Socket Protocol, which describes itself as "the first chain-abstraction protocol," enabling developers to build applications that interact seamlessly across multiple blockchains — not a new blockchain but a network of off-chain and on-chain components that coordinate to execute user intents across different chains.\n\n### Key Features\n\n| Feature | Status | Description |\n|---------|--------|-------------|\n| Social news feed | **Live** | Personalized, news-driven market discovery |\n| 1-tap trading | **Live** | Simplified execution on Polymarket |\n| Cross-chain deposits | **Live** | Supports deposits from Polygon, Solana, BTC, and 10+ EVMs |\n| Leaderboard | **Live** | On-chain leaderboard ranked by real PnL (not wallet size) |\n| Auto-resolving markets | **Live** | No manual claim needed post-resolution |\n| Whale/wallet tracking | **Live** | Net flows feature tracking when multiple tracked wallets start buying the same outcome |\n| Pro Terminal (web) | **Live** | Available at pro.fireplace.gg |\n| Mobile App | **Live** | Consumer-facing app at fireplace.gg |\n| Smart order routing (cross-venue) | **Roadmap** | Fireplace intends to automatically route orders to the best-priced and deepest liquidity pool |\n| Kalshi integration | **Roadmap** | Bridging crypto and regulated venues |\n| Deeper data layers | **Roadmap** | Funding will accelerate deeper data layers and cross-venue aggregation |\n| Advanced order types | **Live/Expanding** | Beyond simple market orders |\n\n### Asset Universe & Scope\nFireplace aggregates data from various prediction platforms into one interface, allowing professional investors to track politics, sports, and economic events in a single location. Currently, the primary integration is with Polymarket, with Kalshi and additional venues planned.\n\n### UX & Technical Architecture\nFireplace operates two interfaces: a **mobile app** (consumer-focused social feed) and a **web-based pro terminal** (institutional-grade). The technical stack leverages Enclave Money for wallet/automation infrastructure and Socket Protocol for chain abstraction. Socket enables users to enjoy seamless transactions without manually switching networks or bridging assets, while developers build cross-chain functionality without needing to integrate every chain separately.\n\n### What's Live vs. Roadmap vs. Vaporware\n- **Live:** Mobile app, pro terminal, Polymarket integration, social feed, wallet tracking, leaderboard, cross-chain deposits\n- **Roadmap:** Cross-venue smart order routing (the most critical differentiating feature), Kalshi integration, advanced analytics layers\n- **Flag:** The cross-venue smart order routing — arguably the feature that most defines the "Bloomberg Terminal" thesis — is not yet fully shipped. This is a critical distinction; the platform today is primarily a Polymarket trading interface with social features, not yet a full-fledged cross-venue aggregator.\n\n---\n\n## Business Model & Economics\n\n### Revenue Streams\nFireplace has not publicly disclosed its revenue model in detail. Based on industry analogs and feature set, likely revenue streams include:\n\n1. **Transaction fees / spread capture** — Taking a fee on trades executed through the platform (similar to TradeFox, which charges a progressive fee structure from 0.95% (Cub tier) to 0.75% (Tradefox Prime))\n2. **Premium terminal subscriptions** — Pro terminal access (common in trading terminal business models)\n3. **Data/API monetization** — Selling aggregated market data and analytics\n4. **Potential future token economics** — Not yet announced but common in crypto-native infrastructure plays\n\n*Note: Revenue model details are not publicly available and should be confirmed during diligence.*\n\n### Unit Economics Context\nFor context on the underlying market economics:\n- Kalshi generated $263.5 million in fee revenue on $22.88 billion in volume, meaning fees represented a little under 1.2% of total volume.\n- Polymarket US charges approximately $10 in fees on $10,000 in positions (0.10% taker fee)\n- An aggregation layer adding even a small fee (10-50bps) on routed volume could generate meaningful revenue as volumes scale\n\n### Growth Trajectory\nIn early 2024, monthly notional prediction market trading volume across all major platforms was below $100 million; it reached over $13 billion in November 2025, with 2025 total activity exceeding $44 billion. This represents a ~130x growth in monthly volumes in under two years.\n\nMonthly active users in prediction markets rose from around 4,000 in 2024 to well over 600,000 by late 2025. This user base expansion creates growing demand for professional tooling.\n\n### Structural Advantages\n- **Asset-light model** — Fireplace sits above prediction markets, not competing with them\n- **Network effects** — Social features and leaderboards create user stickiness\n- **Data moat potential** — Aggregated cross-venue data becomes more valuable over time\n- **Regulatory agnostic** — As an aggregator, can bridge regulated (Kalshi) and crypto (Polymarket) venues\n\n---\n\n## Team & Backers\n\n### Founders\n\n**Sumer Malhotra — Co-founder & CEO**\n- Based in Hong Kong\n- LinkedIn profile indicates connections to J.P. Morgan network and Hong Kong financial ecosystem\n- Educated at The University of Hong Kong\n- Active on X (@buuxbt) with community engagement\n- *Note: While deal notes reference TradFi experience, specific J.P. Morgan employment could not be independently confirmed from public sources. The LinkedIn profile shows J.P. Morgan as a tagged entity but specific role details are behind LinkedIn's paywall.*\n\n**Akshay Rajagopal — Co-founder & CTO**\n- Co-Founder at Fireplace and Co-Founder at Enclave Markets (the wallet infrastructure powering Fireplace).\n- Previous experience includes Engineering Lead for Blockchain and Frontend at Xalts, Software Development Engineer at Amazon, Applied Data Intelligence at MSCI Inc.\n- Educated at BITS Pilani (Birla Institute of Technology and Science).\n- Technical background spanning blockchain engineering, data analytics, and frontend development\n- Also founded Enclave Money, the in-house wallet infrastructure\n\n### Lead Investor: Frachtis\n- Frachtis is a $20 million pre-seed fund launched by Xavier Meegan, former CIO at top staking provider Chorus One, backed by institutional investors such as Theta Capital, along with crypto-native backers including RockawayX, Chorus One, and Cyber Fund.\n- With over 60 investments to date, the team brings a tech and research-driven approach.\n- Fireplace was noted as Frachtis' "first lead investment." This is notable — being the inaugural lead for a new fund means both high conviction and high reputational commitment.\n- Xavier Meegan stated: "Fireplace is building the professional interface that markets like Polymarket have been missing – the data, speed, and tooling that serious traders expect. This will unlock a new category for prediction markets."\n\n### Co-Investor: White Star Capital\n- White Star Capital launched a $120 million Digital Asset Fund to back crypto networks and blockchain-enabled Web3 businesses.\n- International VC firm based in New York, London, Montreal, Paris, Tokyo, and Hong Kong.\n- Notable portfolio includes RedStone, Ledn, ParaSwap, and others\n\n### Syndicate Participation\n- Rounds on **Legion** and **Echo** (crypto-native syndicate platforms), broadening the angel/community investor base\n\n### Hiring Signals\n- The company is hiring across engineering, product, and design. Active hiring at a pre-seed stage signals execution momentum and product velocity.\n- Enclave Money (the underlying wallet infra) has 2-10 employees.\n\n---\n\n## Token/Equity Economics\n\n### Capital Structure\n- **Stage:** Pre-seed\n- **Amount raised:** $1.5M\n- **Valuation:** Not publicly disclosed\n- **Structure:** Likely equity/SAFE (standard for pre-seed crypto startups)\n- **Cap table insight:** Lead investor Frachtis is a $20M fund making this their first lead — a $1.5M round would represent a 7.5% deployment from the fund, suggesting meaningful conviction\n\n### Token Status\n- **No token has been announced.** This is notable for a crypto-native project.\n- Given the use of Enclave Money infrastructure and Socket Protocol partnerships, a future token could be used for governance, fee distribution, or incentive alignment — but this is speculative.\n- The absence of a token at this stage could be viewed positively (focused on product, not financialization) or as a question mark (how will the crypto-native user base be incentivized long-term?)\n\n---\n\n## Competitive Landscape\n\n### Direct Competitors in the Aggregation/Terminal Layer\n\n| Competitor | Description | Funding | Differentiation vs. Fireplace |\n|-----------|-------------|---------|------------------------------|\n| **TradeFox** | Prediction market aggregator and prime brokerage backed by Alliance DAO and CMT Digital | Alliance DAO + CMT Digital backing | Emphasizes leverage trading, prime brokerage; progressive fee structure 0.75%-0.95%; still in beta |\n| **Verso** | Professional-grade prediction market terminal with Bloomberg-style institutional interface for Polymarket and Kalshi | Unknown | Bloomberg-style analytics focus |\n| **Matchr** | Universal prediction market aggregator searching 1500+ markets across platforms with smart routing and automated yield strategies | Unknown | Arbitrage and yield strategy focus |\n| **Bullpen** | On-chain trading terminal combining prediction markets with spot tokens and perpetual futures using Solana's Jupiter Ultra and Hyperliquid | Unknown | Multi-asset terminal (not prediction-only) |\n| **Stand** | Prediction market aggregator and advanced trading terminal for professionals | Unknown | Multi-market view |\n| **Oddpool** | Aggregates live cross-venue odds, spreads, arbitrage opportunities across Polymarket, Kalshi, CME | Unknown | Data/analytics focus |\n\n### Underlying Platforms (Not direct competitors — these are the venues Fireplace aggregates)\n\n| Platform | Valuation | Key Stat |\n|----------|-----------|----------|\n| **Polymarket** | ~$8B (ICE investment) | Over $20B volume in 2025 |\n| **Kalshi** | $11B (Series E) | $263.5 million in fee revenue in 2025 |\n| **FanDuel Predicts** | Part of Flutter ($200-300M investment) | Flutter plans to invest $200-300M into prediction market expansion in 2026 |\n| **Robinhood** | Public company | Launching prediction market exchange with Susquehanna/MIAXdx |\n\n### Defensibility & Moat Analysis\n\n**Potential moats:**\n- **Execution quality** — Smart order routing across venues creates a network/data moat\n- **Social graph** — Leaderboards, wallet tracking, and social features create user stickiness\n- **Cross-chain infrastructure** — Enclave Money + Socket Protocol integration is technically complex to replicate\n- **Data aggregation** — Unified view across fragmented markets has compounding value\n\n**Moat weaknesses:**\n- The aggregation layer is early and crowded — at least 6-8 competitors are building similar products\n- No obvious proprietary data advantage yet (on-chain data is publicly accessible)\n- Underlying platforms (Polymarket, Kalshi) could build or acquire aggregation features\n- The prediction market aggregation tooling space is young and the pace of change is high — pmxt launched in January 2026, PolyRouter is in open beta.\n\n### Market Sizing Reality Check\n\n2025 total prediction market volume exceeded $44 billion. In 2026, markets opened with a new single-day high of ~$701.7 million in trading volume, with weekly totals pushing past $5 billion.\n\nCombined open interest across major platforms increased from about $3.3 billion to nearly $13 billion.\n\nIf Fireplace captures even 1-5% of the prediction market volume through its aggregation layer and charges 10-50bps in fees, the addressable revenue opportunity at current volumes would be:\n- 1% of $44B × 25bps = ~$11M/year\n- 5% of $44B × 25bps = ~$55M/year\n- With volumes potentially doubling in 2026, these numbers scale accordingly\n\nThis assumes Fireplace routes meaningful order flow, which remains to be proven.\n\n---\n\n## Key Metrics & Traction\n\n| Metric | Value | Source | Notes |\n|--------|-------|--------|-------|\n| Waitlist traders | 30,000+ | Self-reported (press release) | Not verified independently |\n| X (Twitter) followers | ~10,500 | Verified via X profile | 10.5K followers as observed on X profile |\n| Polymarket badge | ✅ Official | Self-reported | Indicates platform-level recognition |\n| Public launch date | Jan 27, 2026 | Press release | ~6 weeks live |\n| Pre-seed raised | $1.5M | Multiple press sources | Confirmed by PRNewswire, DeFi Rate, etc. |\n| RootData Popularity Rank | #50 out of 19,413 | RootData project rank: 50/19413 | High relative ranking for a pre-seed project |\n| Active trading volume | Not disclosed | N/A | Key gap in available data |\n| Revenue | Not disclosed | N/A | Pre-revenue or early-revenue stage |\n\n*Note: Most traction metrics are self-reported via the company's press release. Independent verification of actual trading volume and active users is not publicly available.*\n\n---\n\n## Risk Analysis\n\n### Platform/Dependency Risk\n- **HIGH:** Fireplace is critically dependent on Polymarket and Kalshi APIs remaining accessible. If either platform restricts third-party access or builds native aggregation features, Fireplace's core value proposition is at risk.\n- Polymarket acquired Dome API (a precursor to unified prediction market tooling) in 2025, and Kalshi has launched a builder program with grants and API access. Both platforms could internalize or restrict the aggregation layer.\n\n### Regulatory Risk\n- **MEDIUM-HIGH:** Prediction markets face evolving regulatory scrutiny. In January 2026, a Massachusetts court issued a preliminary injunction against Kalshi, banning sports-based betting in the state. A Tennessee Federal Court granted a preliminary injunction protecting Kalshi's sports event contracts, classified as 'swaps' under the Commodity Exchange Act. The regulatory landscape is fluid and jurisdictional fragmentation adds complexity.\n- Fireplace operating from Hong Kong adds regulatory ambiguity — helpful for avoiding US jurisdiction risks but creates questions about long-term US market access.\n\n### Team Execution Risk\n- **MEDIUM:** Two co-founders with relevant but not deeply established track records. CTO Akshay Rajagopal has Amazon and blockchain engineering experience, which is solid. CEO Sumer Malhotra has HK finance connections but no confirmed prior exits or large-scale startup experience.\n- Small team (2-10 people including Enclave Money) must execute across mobile app, web terminal, cross-chain infrastructure, and multiple venue integrations simultaneously.\n\n### Market/Timing Risk\n- **MEDIUM:** The prediction market tooling space is experiencing a Cambrian explosion — dozens of analytics, trading terminal, aggregator, and AI agent tools are emerging simultaneously. Winner-take-most dynamics may apply, and Fireplace is one of many contenders.\n- Conversely, the rapid market growth means the pie is expanding faster than competitors can divide it.\n\n### Financial/Dilution Risk\n- **LOW (current):** $1.5M pre-seed is a small raise. Future rounds will likely be needed within 12-18 months, and valuation will depend on traction metrics.\n- If the team cannot demonstrate meaningful trading volume routed through the platform before the next raise, valuation compression is a risk.\n\n---\n\n## Investment Considerations\n\n### Bull Case 🐂\n1. **Massive TAM expansion:** Prediction market monthly volumes grew from <$100M in early 2024 to $13B+ by late 2025 — a 130x increase. If this trajectory continues, even a small share of volume creates a large business.\n2. **Infrastructure layer positioning:** Fireplace doesn't compete with prediction markets — it enables them. Capital is flowing into three layers simultaneously: regulated exchanges, crypto venues, and now infrastructure tools. The infrastructure play often has the best risk/reward.\n3. **Bloomberg Terminal analog is proven:** In traditional finance, Bloomberg generates ~$12B/year in revenue sitting above exchanges. The prediction market equivalent is an untapped opportunity.\n4. **Smart order routing is genuine alpha:** In traditional finance, smart order routing is table stakes; in prediction markets, this layer barely exists. First-mover advantage in cross-venue routing could create sticky user behavior.\n5. **Strong lead investor conviction:** Frachtis made Fireplace their first-ever lead investment from a $20M fund, indicating deep diligence and thesis alignment. White Star Capital ($120M+ DAF) participation adds institutional credibility.\n\n### Bear Case 🐻\n1. **Feature, not a company:** The aggregation/terminal layer may be a feature that underlying platforms (Polymarket, Kalshi, Robinhood) build natively, rather than a standalone business. Polymarket already acquired Dome API, suggesting interest in internalizing tooling.\n2. **Crowded nascent space:** At least 6-8 direct competitors are building prediction market terminals/aggregators (TradeFox, Verso, Matchr, Bullpen, Stand, Oddpool, etc.), many with comparable or stronger backing. Differentiation is unclear.\n3. **No revenue visibility:** No public revenue model details, no disclosed trading volume metrics, and the core differentiating feature (cross-venue smart order routing) is still on the roadmap, not shipped.\n4. **API dependency risk:** Fireplace's entire product depends on continued API access to underlying platforms. One API restriction could devastate the product overnight. This is an existential risk for aggregators.\n5. **Team scale concerns:** A 2-10 person team building simultaneously across mobile app, web terminal, cross-chain wallet infrastructure, and multi-venue integration is extremely ambitious. Execution risk is high relative to the breadth of the product vision.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\n### Net Assessment\nFireplace is positioned in the right space at the right time. The prediction market ecosystem has clearly crossed into institutional-scale territory, and the infrastructure tooling layer is genuinely underbuilt. The "Bloomberg Terminal for prediction markets" thesis is compelling in theory.\n\nHowever, the gap between vision and current product is significant. Today, Fireplace is primarily a social trading interface for Polymarket — the cross-venue aggregation and smart order routing that would truly differentiate it remain on the roadmap. The competitive landscape is more crowded than the deal card suggests, with at least half a dozen funded competitors building similar products.\n\nThe investment ultimately rests on:\n1. Can this team ship cross-venue routing before competitors?\n2. Will underlying platforms allow aggregator access long-term?\n3. Can Fireplace convert waitlist interest into active trading volume?\n\n### Key Open Questions for Further Diligence\n- **What is the actual revenue model?** Fee structure, pricing tiers, and unit economics need to be clarified\n- **What is the current active trading volume on the platform?** Waitlist numbers ≠ active traders\n- **What is the timeline for cross-venue smart order routing?** This is the core differentiator — when does it ship?\n- **What are the API agreements with Polymarket and Kalshi?** Are there formal partnerships or is Fireplace building on public APIs that could be restricted?\n- **What is the valuation on this round?** $1.5M at what valuation determines the risk/reward equation\n- **What is CEO Sumer Malhotra's specific professional background?** J.P. Morgan association appears on LinkedIn but role/duration are not independently confirmed\n- **What is the burn rate and runway?** $1.5M at a small team should provide 12-18 months, but this needs confirmation\n- **Is there a token planned?** Token economics would significantly change the investment thesis\n\n### What Metrics to Watch Going Forward\n1. **Monthly active traders** (not waitlist — actual traders placing orders)\n2. **Volume routed through the platform** (most critical KPI)\n3. **Cross-venue routing launch date** and adoption metrics\n4. **User retention / DAU/MAU ratio** — social features should drive this\n5. **Competitive landscape evolution** — watch for TradeFox, Verso, and Matchr traction\n6. **Platform API policy changes** from Polymarket and Kalshi\n7. **Hiring velocity** — team scale needs to grow quickly to execute the vision\n\n### Recommended Next Steps for the Investment Team\n1. **Request product demo** of both mobile app and pro terminal to assess current product quality\n2. **Verify trading volume data** — ask for actual platform metrics beyond waitlist\n3. **Clarify revenue model and valuation** — essential for investment decision\n4. **Deep-dive on API dependency** — understand formal vs. informal relationships with Polymarket/Kalshi\n5. **Technical diligence on Enclave Money** — this is the proprietary infrastructure layer and needs independent assessment\n6. **Competitive positioning call** — speak with Xavier Meegan (Frachtis) on why they chose Fireplace over TradeFox and other competitors\n7. **Reference checks** on founding team — confirm CEO background, CTO's technical capabilities via former colleagues at Amazon/Xalts	complete	2026-03-09 09:00:41.433124
c50de620-504d-455c-916f-68e5c24c8845	b42d2a15-8eeb-4bcd-95f2-d920edfb373b	1e9bf641-c93c-4629-906a-f50db9050164	PredictParity (Parity) — Deep Research Report	# PredictParity (Parity) — Deep Research Report\n\n**Cross-platform prediction market aggregator enabling users to trade, track top traders, and analyze market data across multiple prediction market venues.**\n\n**Website:** https://predictparity.com\n\n**Built by MovieTime (@MovieTimeDev) | No external backers disclosed | Pre-launch phase**\n\n---\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nPredictParity, branded as "Parity," is a pre-launch prediction market aggregator that aims to provide a unified interface for trading, tracking, and analyzing prediction markets across multiple platforms such as Polymarket and Kalshi. The platform's stated value proposition is to let users "trade prediction markets across platforms," "track top traders, analyze market data, and make informed decisions." The company is led by a pseudonymous founder known as "MovieTime" (@MovieTimeDev), who has built a following in the prediction markets community but whose real identity and professional background remain unknown. As of the latest available data, the @PredictParity Twitter account was created in September 2025, has 2,860 followers, and has not posted any content. The profile explicitly states "NO COIN," distancing from token-based models.\n\nThe prediction market industry represents a massive and rapidly growing addressable market. Total notional trading volume across prediction markets reached over $44 billion in 2025. Kalshi raised $1 billion at an $11 billion valuation in December 2025, while Polymarket received a $2 billion strategic investment from Intercontinental Exchange at a $9 billion post-money valuation. An aggregator layer that unifies access to these fragmented venues addresses a real pain point — but PredictParity enters this race in a pre-product state while at least half a dozen funded competitors are already shipping. No funding, no product, no team details, and no public roadmap have been disclosed. This is a concept-stage opportunity at the earliest possible diligence threshold.\n\n---\n\n## Product Overview\n\n### Core Product\n\nPredictParity's product is not yet live. The @PredictParity Twitter account states the company is "Balancing Prediction Markets" but "hasn't posted" any content. The landing page at predictparity.com is minimal — it states only that the platform will let users "trade prediction markets across platforms" and "track top traders, analyze market data, and make informed decisions."\n\nBased on the founder's public commentary and the stated positioning, the product vision appears to encompass:\n\n1. **Cross-platform trading execution** — Placing trades on Polymarket, Kalshi, and potentially other venues from a single interface\n2. **Trader tracking / copy trading** — Following and replicating the trades of top-performing prediction market traders\n3. **Market data analytics** — Aggregated odds, arbitrage detection, and market intelligence across venues\n\nHowever, **no screenshots, demos, beta access, API documentation, or technical architecture details have been publicly shared.** The product remains entirely conceptual.\n\n### Asset Universe / Scope\n\nNot publicly available. Based on the stated vision of cross-platform aggregation, the platform would likely cover the same categories as its underlying venues:\n\n| Venue | Key Categories | Status on Parity |\n|-------|---------------|-----------------|\n| Polymarket | Politics, sports, crypto, culture, economics | ⏳ Presumed target |\n| Kalshi | Sports, politics, economics, weather | ⏳ Presumed target |\n| Opinion | Macro, crypto, culture, TGE events | ⏳ Unknown |\n| Limitless, Myriad, SxBet | Various | ⏳ Unknown |\n\n### UX, Tooling & Technical Architecture\n\nNo information available. There are no public details about whether the platform will be web-based, mobile, use a custom front-end, or integrate existing APIs. The technical stack is entirely undisclosed.\n\n### Additional Products / Roadmap\n\n| Feature | Status |\n|---------|--------|\n| Cross-platform trading | ⏳ No ship date |\n| Trader tracking | ⏳ No ship date |\n| Market analytics | ⏳ No ship date |\n| Mobile app | ⏳ Unknown |\n| API access | ⏳ Unknown |\n\n**Everything is vaporware at this stage.** There is no public roadmap, no changelog, no beta program, and no feature timeline.\n\n---\n\n## Business Model & Economics\n\n### Revenue Streams\n\nNot disclosed. Potential revenue models for prediction market aggregators, based on competitor analysis, include:\n\n1. **Trading fees / commissions** — TradeFox, for example, charges a "progressive fee structure from 0.95% (Cub tier) to 0.75% (Tradefox Prime), with corresponding cashback rewards up to 0.25%."\n2. **Subscription tiers** — Analytics-focused platforms like Oddpool offer freemium and Pro subscription models\n3. **Copy trading fees** — Taking a percentage of profits from copy-traded positions\n4. **Data/API licensing** — Selling aggregated prediction market data to institutions\n5. **Referral revenue** — Earning commissions from platforms for routing order flow\n\n### On-Chain / Technical Execution Model\n\nUnknown. Cross-platform prediction market aggregation requires different integration approaches depending on the venue: Polymarket operates on-chain on Polygon using CLOB smart contracts, while Kalshi is a centralized, CFTC-regulated exchange with a traditional API. As described in an industry technical analysis, "Polymarket is crypto-native, settles on-chain, runs globally" while "Kalshi is CFTC-regulated, centralized, US-only." Bridging both requires distinct technical architectures for each integration.\n\n### Unit Economics\n\nThe aggregator business in prediction markets is nascent, making unit economics difficult to model. Key structural considerations include:\n\n- **Zero-fee environment on underlying platforms**: Polymarket "did not charge fees on deposits, withdrawals, or trades during 2025, instead subsidizing liquidity through maker incentives." It only began introducing taker fees in January 2026 in select markets. This makes it difficult for aggregators to layer additional fees without degrading price competitiveness.\n- **Volume concentration among power users**: Data shows that "the average notional traded per account" rose to $4,800 per month, "indicating deeper engagement from a smaller 'power user' cohort," suggesting the addressable paying customer base is narrow.\n- **Skewed profitability**: Research indicates "most users ultimately lost money, while a small set of professional operators captured the bulk of positive PnL through systematic strategies."\n\n---\n\n## Team & Backers\n\n### MovieTime (Founder)\n\nMovieTime (@MovieTimeDev) is the sole known person behind PredictParity. The account has approximately 5,508 followers (up from ~2,860 on the @PredictParity account). The founder operates pseudonymously — no real name, employment history, educational background, or prior founding history is publicly available.\n\n**Domain Expertise Signals:**\n\nMovieTime has demonstrated meaningful domain expertise in prediction markets through public content:\n\n- Shared analysis such as "How accurate is Polymarket? 89% accurate 1 week out, but in the final 4 hours it jumps to 95% accuracy right before resolution."\n- Highlighted that "78% of Polymarket events resolve 'NO' meaning markets consistently overprice unlikely events."\n- Published detailed prediction market arbitrage tutorials, explaining strategies like buying YES at $0.19 and NO at $0.77 for guaranteed profit. One such arbitrage post received 25.6K views.\n- Curated lists of top prediction market traders, demonstrating deep network connections within the community.\n- Content has been syndicated on OKX, noting that "Prediction markets did 180% more volume than Solana Memecoins."\n- Described activity like "scraping tiktok virality to frontrun political prediction markets," suggesting technical capability.\n\n**Key Concerns:**\n\n- **Pseudonymity**: No ability to verify professional background, track record, or accountability\n- **Solo founder**: No evidence of a co-founder, engineering team, or advisors\n- **Content creator vs. builder gap**: Strong content presence does not necessarily translate to product-building capability — no shipping history is visible\n- **No prior ventures**: No public record of previously shipped products or companies\n\n### Backers\n\n**None disclosed.** There is no publicly known funding, no disclosed investors, and no acceleration program participation. The "NO COIN" designation on the profile suggests the founder is not pursuing a token-based model, which could indicate intent to pursue traditional equity funding, but this is speculative.\n\n### Build-in-Public / Community Signals\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|--------|-------|\n| @PredictParity Twitter followers | ~2,860 |\n| @PredictParity tweets | 0 (no content posted) |\n| @MovieTimeDev followers | ~5,508 |\n| @MovieTimeDev engagement | Individual posts reaching 25K+ views, some reaching 543K+ views |\n| Discord | Not publicly available |\n| Product waitlist | Not publicly available |\n| GitHub | Not publicly available |\n\nThird-party community members have flagged PredictParity as a "prediction project to follow," indicating nascent grassroots interest. However, the complete absence of content on the @PredictParity account and the lack of any product demonstration represent significant signal deficits.\n\n---\n\n## Token Economics\n\n**Not applicable.** The @PredictParity profile explicitly states "NO COIN," distancing the project from any token or cryptocurrency component. This is notable given the crypto-adjacent nature of the prediction market space and represents either a genuine strategic choice to pursue a fee-based SaaS model, or a statement that could change at a later date. This section is included for completeness — if a token is introduced later, it should be evaluated independently.\n\n---\n\n## Competitive Landscape\n\nThe prediction market aggregator/tooling space has exploded in 2025–2026. As one technical analysis notes, "This category barely existed eighteen months ago. As of early 2026, at least three distinct products occupy it, with more likely to follow." PredictParity enters an already crowded field without a live product.\n\n### Funded / Established Competitors\n\n| Competitor | Description | Funding/Backing | Status | Key Differentiator |\n|-----------|-------------|----------------|--------|-------------------|\n| **TradeFox** | Prediction market aggregator + prime brokerage | Alliance DAO + CMT Digital ($500M AUM) | Private beta | Institutional-grade execution, leverage, self-custody |\n| **Oddpool** | "The Bloomberg for prediction markets" | Not publicly disclosed | Live (freemium + Pro) | Cross-venue analytics, arb scanner, whale tracking, API |\n| **Stand** | Prediction market aggregator + trading terminal | Not publicly disclosed | Live; $16.44M monthly DEX volume in January 2026 | Copy trading, counter-trading, multi-market view |\n| **Matchr** | Universal aggregator searching 1,500+ markets with smart routing | Not publicly disclosed | Live | Best-price execution, yield strategies |\n| **Verso** | Bloomberg-style institutional interface for prediction markets | Not publicly disclosed | Live | Professional terminal UX |\n| **Polynance** | Aggregator with SDK | Not publicly disclosed | Live (SDK) | Developer-first, programmatic access |\n| **pmxt** | Open-source SDK normalizing data + execution across Polymarket, Kalshi, and Limitless | Open source | Launched January 2026 | CCXT-style unified API layer |\n\n### Major Prediction Market Platforms (Parity's Upstream Dependencies)\n\n| Platform | Valuation | 2025 Volume | Key Event |\n|----------|-----------|-------------|-----------|\n| Polymarket | $9B post-money | $21.5 billion | $2B ICE investment (Oct 2025) |\n| Kalshi | $11B valuation | ~$17.1 billion | $1B Series E (Dec 2025) |\n| Opinion | ~$25M raised | ~1/3 of global prediction market volume | $20M pre-Series A (Feb 2026) |\n\n### Competitive Advantages (Potential)\n\n- **"NO COIN" positioning**: In a space where many aggregators are building token-based models (which can create misaligned incentives), a clean, fee-based approach could appeal to serious traders\n- **Founder's community credibility**: MovieTime's authentic, trader-centric voice and deep prediction market knowledge could serve as a distribution moat if converted into product loyalty\n- **Timing with market growth**: Total prediction market volume exceeded $44 billion in 2025 and continues accelerating — significant market tailwinds remain\n\n### Competitive Risks\n\n- **Late entrant with no product**: Multiple competitors are live and shipping features while PredictParity has zero public product presence\n- **No funding vs. funded competitors**: TradeFox is backed by Alliance DAO and CMT Digital; Oddpool and Stand are live with revenue; PredictParity has no disclosed capital\n- **Low barriers to entry**: An integration-first product layer can be built for as little as "$30k–$120k," meaning the tooling itself is not a significant moat\n- **Platform dependency**: Any aggregator is entirely dependent on API access from Polymarket and Kalshi, who could restrict or revoke access at any time, or build competing features natively\n\n---\n\n## Key Metrics & Traction\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|--------|-------|--------|\n| Product status | Pre-launch, no product available | PredictParity website |\n| @PredictParity followers | ~2,860 | Twitter |\n| @PredictParity posts | 0 | Twitter |\n| @MovieTimeDev followers | ~5,508 | Twitter |\n| @MovieTimeDev peak post views | 543K+ | Twitter |\n| Funding raised | $0 (none disclosed) | N/A |\n| Team size | 1 (pseudonymous) | Public info |\n| Revenue | $0 | N/A |\n| Users / waitlist | Unknown | N/A |\n\n**Context**: These metrics are below the threshold typically expected even at pre-seed stage. For comparison, TradeFox, also an early-stage prediction market aggregator, has ~9,766 followers and is in beta with active users. Stand reached $16.44 million in monthly DEX volume in January 2026, demonstrating that competitors have already achieved meaningful traction. PredictParity has no comparable data points.\n\n---\n\n## Risk Analysis\n\n### Platform/Dependency Risk\n\nPredictParity's entire value proposition depends on maintaining API access to Polymarket, Kalshi, and other prediction market venues. This creates a critical single point of failure. Both major platforms are actively developing their own builder ecosystems — Polymarket acquired Dome API in 2025, and Kalshi launched a builder program with grants and API access. The platforms themselves could vertically integrate the aggregation features PredictParity aims to offer, or could restrict third-party access to protect their own user relationships. Historical precedent in crypto is clear: exchanges have routinely shut down APIs to third-party traders and tools when those tools threatened their control over order flow or user data. Additionally, competitors like Gemini, Crypto.com, and DraftKings are entering prediction markets directly, meaning the landscape could shift dramatically in ways that disadvantage thin aggregation layers.\n\n### Regulatory Risk\n\nThe prediction market industry is facing an unprecedented regulatory confrontation. As one analysis notes, "prediction markets will operate in a dual regulatory reality — federally legitimized under the CFTC but resisted at the state level in multiple states" until the Supreme Court resolves the issue. Sports-related event contracts account for over 90% of Kalshi's activity, and Nevada has already sued and obtained a temporary restraining order against Kalshi. Massachusetts sued Kalshi in September 2025, and a court "rejected Kalshi's argument that its contracts are CFTC-regulated swaps rather than sports bets." If state regulators succeed in restricting prediction market platforms, the entire addressable market for aggregators shrinks dramatically. For an aggregator without its own regulatory status, this risk is amplified — it inherits the regulatory exposure of every platform it integrates with.\n\n### Team Execution Risk\n\nThis is arguably the most significant risk factor. The founder is pseudonymous, meaning there is no way to verify their ability to recruit engineers, close funding, navigate partnerships with major platforms, or build enterprise-quality software. Content creation and community building are demonstrably different skills from product management, engineering leadership, and business operations. While MovieTime demonstrates genuine domain expertise, prediction markets are a domain where "profitability was extremely skewed" and "returns concentrate among participants with superior tooling, data edges, and execution discipline" — building that tooling requires a very different skill set than trading analysis. The sole-founder, pseudonymous, zero-employee model at concept stage is a high-risk profile that would typically require exceptional compensating factors (deep technical demo, viral traction, strategic backer) to justify investment.\n\n### Market Timing / Window Risk\n\nThe prediction market aggregator category is maturing rapidly. As one analysis notes, aggregator arbitrage strategies "may compress in 2026 as aggregators mature." Industry observers describe the space as following "the same maturation path crypto exchanges took between 2018 and 2022" and predict that "within 12–24 months, the aggregator category will look materially different." PredictParity's pre-launch status means it may miss the critical window during which early entrants establish user habits, integrate with platforms, and build data moats. Every month without shipping allows competitors to accumulate users, trade data, and ecosystem partnerships that create switching costs.\n\n### Market Sizing Reality Check\n\nWhile prediction markets are growing rapidly, the tooling/aggregator layer captures only a thin margin of the overall volume. Stand, one of the more successful aggregators, reached $16.44 million in monthly DEX volume — meaningful but representing a tiny fraction of the $44 billion in total 2025 volume. The aggregator TAM is a derivative of the platform TAM, filtered through willingness to pay for premium tools. Only 0.51% of Polymarket wallets had PnL exceeding $1,000, and only 1.74% of accounts had over $50,000 in trading volume. The paying user base for professional prediction market tools is likely in the low thousands globally — a challenging foundation for venture-scale returns.\n\n---\n\n## Investment Considerations\n\n### Bull Case\n\n- **Massive market tailwinds**: Prediction market volume exceeded $44 billion in 2025, and Kalshi and Polymarket alone raised $3.71 billion in venture funding in 2025. The underlying market is growing orders of magnitude faster than most crypto verticals. If even a fraction of this growth continues, aggregation tools will be essential infrastructure.\n\n- **Authentic founder-market fit**: MovieTime is genuinely embedded in the prediction market community, understands trader pain points firsthand, and has demonstrated the ability to identify cross-platform arbitrage opportunities and analyze platform mechanics at a level that shows deep domain immersion. This is the type of founder who could build something traders actually want.\n\n- **"NO COIN" as a differentiator**: In a space saturated with token-launch projects that often prioritize speculation over product, a clean, utility-first approach could attract serious traders and eventually institutional users who are repelled by token mechanics. This positioning could also attract traditional fintech investors who are wary of crypto-native business models.\n\n- **Pre-seed entry price**: If one believes in the founder's ability to execute, the extremely early stage represents the lowest possible valuation entry point. The aggregator layer in prediction markets is analogous to CCXT or DEX aggregators in crypto trading — categories that eventually produced significant winners.\n\n- **Fragmentation is increasing**: Competitors like Gemini, Crypto.com, and DraftKings are entering prediction markets, and platforms like Opinion are growing fast. The more venues that launch, the stronger the value proposition for aggregation becomes.\n\n### Bear Case\n\n- **Zero product, zero traction, zero team**: PredictParity has not shipped anything. There is no product, no revenue, no users, no waitlist, no funding, and no disclosed team beyond a single pseudonymous founder. This is below the threshold of most pre-seed investments, which typically require at least a prototype or strong technical co-founder.\n\n- **Already behind multiple funded competitors**: TradeFox has Alliance DAO and CMT Digital backing, Stand has $16M+ monthly volume, Oddpool has a live product with API, and pmxt provides open-source SDK infrastructure. PredictParity would need to differentiate against established and funded players from a standing start — an extremely difficult position.\n\n- **Pseudonymous founder is a fundamental diligence blocker**: For a pre-seed investment where almost the entire bet is on the founder's ability to execute, pseudonymity creates an unresolvable information asymmetry. You cannot verify experience, check references, assess the cap table, or enforce governance without knowing who you're investing in. This is a structural issue, not a personality one.\n\n- **Thin aggregator margins in a zero-fee environment**: Polymarket charged zero trading fees for most of 2025. Layering aggregator fees on top of venues that themselves are competing on cost is structurally challenging. With wash trading estimated at 25% of Polymarket volume, even the headline market size figures may overstate genuine user activity.\n\n- **Regulatory environment could collapse the underlying market**: Prediction markets face a "dual regulatory reality" with active state lawsuits and federal-state jurisdiction conflicts. Supreme Court review may be necessary to resolve the issue. If states succeed in restricting platforms — particularly sports-related markets that drive 90%+ of Kalshi's volume — the entire addressable market for aggregation tools contracts sharply.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nPredictParity occupies an interesting conceptual position in the rapidly growing prediction market ecosystem, led by a founder with genuine domain credibility. However, it is functionally pre-concept: there is no product, no team, no funding, no roadmap, and no public development activity. The prediction market aggregator space has evolved from nascent to competitive in the past 12 months, with multiple funded and shipping competitors. At the current state, PredictParity represents a pre-seed concept bet on a single pseudonymous individual's ability to recruit a team, raise capital, build a product, and compete against better-resourced incumbents — all while the window for first-mover advantage narrows.\n\n### Key Open Questions for Further Diligence\n\n- **Who is MovieTime?** Unmasking the founder's real identity and professional background is essential for any investment. Prior engineering experience, product management history, and team-building track record are all unknown.\n- **Is there a working prototype?** Has any code been written? Is there a private alpha, even in minimal form? The gap between Twitter profile and shipped product is the single most important data point.\n- **What is the technical integration strategy?** Does the founder intend to build on existing SDKs (pmxt, Polynance) or develop custom integrations? The approach determines both timeline and capital requirements.\n- **What is the go-to-market beyond the founder's Twitter following?** 5,500 followers is a starting point, not a distribution moat. How does the platform plan to acquire traders?\n- **Has there been any conversation with Polymarket or Kalshi about API access or builder program participation?** Platform relationship depth is a critical enabler and risk mitigant.\n\n### What Metric to Watch\n\nThe only meaningful signal to monitor is **product launch** — specifically, whether PredictParity ships any functional product (even a bare-bones analytics dashboard or arbitrage scanner) in the next 3–6 months. In the aggregator category, the gap between "concept" and "live product" is the decisive filter. If no product materializes by Q3 2026, the opportunity will have likely been captured by existing competitors.	complete	2026-03-09 13:40:42.431709
236d0e5d-fedf-4f29-9824-49cf276dce0f	cf7b4843-c645-4e2e-a206-b674f04a08ec	1e9bf641-c93c-4629-906a-f50db9050164	Nous Research — Deep Research Report	# Nous Research — Deep Research Report\n\n**Open-source AI research lab building world-class language models and decentralized training infrastructure on Solana.**\n\n**https://nousresearch.com**\n\n**Built by Jeffrey Quesnelle, Karan Malhotra, Teknium & Shivani Mitra | Backed by Paradigm, Delphi Digital, Distributed Global, North Island Ventures | Powered by Solana**\n\n---\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nNous Research is a decentralized AI startup developing open-source, neutrally-aligned large language models and pioneering infrastructure for distributed AI training over the internet. The company positions itself as a leader in the American open-source AI movement, training world-class open-source language models and building infrastructure to coordinate distributed, unbiased training. Its core thesis centers on an alternative to both closed-source AI labs (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google) and the centralized compute paradigm that underpins modern frontier model training. Its stated mission is to advance human rights and freedoms by creating and proliferating open-source language models, supporting their unrestricted availability and use.\n\nThe significance of Nous Research lies at the convergence of two powerful trends: the growing demand for open-source AI alternatives and the crypto/blockchain movement toward decentralized physical infrastructure (DePIN). Nous is a decentralized AI startup using the Solana blockchain as a key component in the process it uses to train its open-source models. Its DeMo/DisTrO technology represents a genuine research breakthrough — the DeMo paper has been accepted to ICLR 2026, developed by @bloc97_ and @theemozilla, and helped kickstart industry research into communication-efficient optimizers. This gives Nous Research scientific credibility rare among crypto-AI projects.\n\nAfter operating mostly under the radar for two years, Nous raised a $50 million Series A round, financed almost entirely by the crypto venture giant Paradigm, valuing Nous at a token valuation of $1 billion. Total funding stands at $65 million, with $50 million led by Paradigm and an additional $15 million that includes a previously unannounced June 2024 round. Hermes 3 has surpassed 50 million downloads, powering agents across platforms like X, Telegram and gaming environments. The Psyche Network testnet launched in May 2025, and Hermes 4.3 became the first production model post-trained entirely on the Psyche network.\n\n---\n\n## Product Overview\n\n### Core Product: Open-Source Language Models (Hermes Series)\n\nNous Research's most prominent product line is the Hermes series of fine-tuned language models, which have established the company's credibility in the open-source AI community. Nous Research has succeeded in creating highly-steerable models through the Hermes series of fine-tunes. The Hermes philosophy is unique in the LLM landscape: Hermes 4 expands Nous Research's line of neutrally-aligned and steerable models with a new group of hybrid reasoners, designed to adhere to the user's needs and system prompts, rather than to a company's ethics code.\n\nThe model family has evolved through multiple generations:\n\n- **Hermes 1 (2023):** Fine-tuned on over 300,000 instructions from Llama 13b, the result was an enhanced model that rivals GPT-3.5-turbo in performance across a variety of tasks.\n- **Hermes 2 (2024):** Trained over the Mixtral 8x7B MoE LLM on over 1,000,000 entries of primarily GPT-4 generated data, achieving state-of-the-art performance on a variety of tasks.\n- **Hermes 3 (August 2024):** Fine-tuned off Meta's Llama 3.1, it achieved competitive results that rivaled much larger proprietary models whilst staying true to the ethos of objectivity and neutrality.\n- **Hermes 4 (August 2025):** A frontier, hybrid-mode reasoning model based on Llama-3.1-70B. Post-training corpus expanded to ~5M samples / ~60B tokens blended across reasoning and non-reasoning data. The largest 405B parameter model scored 96.3% on the MATH-500 benchmark and 81.9% on the AIME'24 mathematics competition.\n- **Hermes 4.3 (December 2025):** Trained with an extended context length (up to 512K) and nearly matches the performance of Hermes 4 70B at half the parameter cost, based on Seed-OSS-36B-Base.\n\n### Psyche Network: Decentralized Training Infrastructure\n\nPsyche is an open infrastructure that democratizes AI development by decentralizing training across underutilized hardware, building on DisTrO and its predecessor DeMo, reducing data transfer by several orders of magnitude, with coordination happening on the Solana blockchain for fault-tolerant and censorship-resistant operation.\n\nThe Psyche Network operates through three participant types:\n- **Coordinators:** The coordinator acts as an authority for the state of the training run and lives on-chain in a smart contract, storing metadata about the run and the list of participants.\n- **Clients:** GPU nodes responsible for performing training computations\n- **Data Providers:** Supply batches of data for training\n\nBuilt on Solana, the network coordinates heterogeneous compute (4090s, A100s, H100s) to join together and train censorship-resistant models in a fault-tolerant manner. The Psyche Network utilizes Nous's DisTrO technology, which reduces inter-GPU communication for AI model training by 1,000-10,000x.\n\nA critical validation milestone: The Hermes 4.3 training run averaged 144k tokens/second spread across 24 Psyche nodes. Using DisTrO's overlapped collective strategy, the entirety of the P2P communications were hidden by the training time, effectively achieving equivalent throughput to traditional, centralized training. Furthermore, the Psyche-trained version of Hermes 4.3 outperformed the traditional centralized version on a suite of downstream tasks.\n\n### DeMo / DisTrO: Core Technology\n\nDeMo (Decoupled Momentum Optimization) and its successor DisTrO (Distributed Training Over-the-Internet) form the foundational technology enabling Nous's decentralized training vision. They further reduced bandwidth by quantizing the Discrete Cosine Transform of momentums — sending just the sign (positive or negative) without magnitude compressed results by more than 3x. DisTrO results grow sub-linearly to model parameter size, meaning as it is applied to larger models, communication latency will, in theory, not be a bottleneck as they scale.\n\n### Consilience 40B: Flagship Pre-Training Run\n\nThe first run on Psyche pretrained a 40B parameter model using the Multi-head Latent Attention (MLA) architecture across 20T tokens, named Consilience, representing the largest pretraining run conducted over the internet to date. The architecture uses DeepSeek v3 + MLA (Dense version without MoE routers), with pretraining data being a merge of FineWeb, FineWeb 2, and The Stack v2. The goal with Consilience is to make a true "base" model — one representative of the entirety of the creative output of humanity, not merely trying to win the benchmarking game.\n\n### Atropos: Open-Source Reinforcement Learning Framework\n\nAtropos is a robust, scalable framework for Reinforcement Learning Environments with LLMs, providing a flexible, scalable, and standardized platform to accelerate LLM-based RL research across diverse, interactive settings. Atropos has proven its value through the NousCoder-14B release: a competitive olympiad programming model post-trained on Qwen3-14B via reinforcement learning, achieving a Pass@1 accuracy of 67.87% on LiveCodeBench v6, up 7.08% from the baseline.\n\n### NousCoder-14B\n\nWhat distinguishes the NousCoder-14B release is its radical openness — Nous Research published not just the model weights but the complete reinforcement learning environment, benchmark suite, and training harness. Trained on 24k verifiable coding problems using 48 B200s over the course of four days.\n\n### Hermes Agent\n\nNous Research open-sourced Hermes Agent, featuring multi-level memory and persistent SSH/Docker/local access for long-running agent workflows, targeting two systemic bottlenecks: memory decay and environmental isolation.\n\n### Additional Products & Roadmap\n\n| Feature | Status |\n|---------|--------|\n| Hermes 4.3 (36B) | ✅ Live (Dec 2025) |\n| Hermes 4 (70B, 405B) | ✅ Live (Aug 2025) |\n| NousCoder-14B | ✅ Live (Jan 2026) |\n| Atropos RL Framework | ✅ Live |\n| Psyche Network (Testnet) | ✅ Live (May 2025) |\n| Consilience 40B Pre-training | ✅ Completed |\n| Hermes Agent | ✅ Live (Feb 2026) |\n| Nous Chat (Web App) | ✅ Live |\n| Nous API (Portal) | ✅ Live |\n| Psyche Network (Mainnet) | ⏳ Coming Soon (no public date) |\n| NOUS Token Launch | ⏳ Coming Soon (no public date) |\n| Distributed RL on Psyche | ⏳ Coming Soon |\n| Nous-Forge (AI Orchestration) | ⏳ Listed in 2024, no public ship date |\n\n---\n\n## Business Model & Economics\n\n### Revenue Streams\n\nNous Research's current revenue model appears to still be in its formative stages, which is typical for a Series A research lab. The identifiable revenue streams include:\n\n1. **API Access (Nous Portal):** Nous Research offers an account and API key management portal, suggesting a pay-per-use inference model for accessing Hermes models.\n\n2. **Nous Chat:** A consumer-facing chat application offering access to Hermes models. While partially free, premium tiers likely exist or are planned.\n\n3. **Future Token Economics:** Nous plans to use Solana as a reward distribution network whereby coordinators track client contributions and assign a points-based system to verify work, with points redeemable for Nous tokens via a treasurer smart contract.\n\n4. **Compute Network Fees:** Once Psyche reaches mainnet, Nous could extract fees from the coordination and matching of compute supply/demand.\n\n### On-Chain / Technical Execution Model\n\nThe Psyche Network's technical architecture is fundamentally differentiated from other decentralized AI approaches. Psyche implements DisTrO in a Rust-based system with P2P networking that is designed to coordinate multiple runs at any given time. The key architectural choice — building on Solana rather than Ethereum — is strategic: Solana's high throughput and low transaction costs make it an ideal platform for handling distributed training micro-transactions.\n\nThe execution model is genuinely novel. Unlike decentralized compute marketplaces (Render, Akash) that simply broker GPU access, Psyche provides a complete distributed *training* infrastructure with consensus-level coordination. This is technically much harder but also much more valuable if it works at scale.\n\n### Unit Economics\n\nThe unit economics of decentralized AI training remain unproven at scale. Currently, there are no results or information that show DeMo and DisTrO's cost efficiency compared to centralized data centers. Metrics like inter-GPU data transfer reductions, cost per token trained, convergence times and global GPU participation reliability will be required for evaluation, but this information is not publicly disclosed. However, some estimates suggest open-source accelerators could achieve 70% cost savings compared to closed labs, though this claim requires independent verification.\n\nThe fundamental economic advantage of the model — utilizing idle GPUs worldwide — has a compelling theoretical basis. Enormous amounts of computing power sit idle or underutilized worldwide. If Nous can successfully tap into even a fraction of this, the cost-per-FLOP could significantly undercut centralized alternatives.\n\n---\n\n## Team & Backers\n\n### Core Founding Team\n\n**Jeffrey Quesnelle — Co-founder & CEO**\n\nQuesnelle holds an M.S. in Computer Science from the University of Michigan-Dearborn, with undergraduate degrees in Computer Science and Mathematics from Oakland University. His interests span AI, cryptocurrencies (especially MEV), and theology. He is the co-founder and CEO of Nous Research. From 2017 to June 2022, he served as Director of Software Development at Intrepid Control Systems, directing strategy and implementation of in-vehicle networking solutions. He co-authored "Automotive Ethernet - The Definitive Guide." His crypto experience comes from his role as Principal Engineer at Eden Network since May 2021.\n\nQuesnelle's background is atypical for an AI lab CEO: deep systems engineering and blockchain/MEV expertise, but not traditional AI research credentials (no PhD, no prior ML publications before Nous). However, his technical breadth has proven valuable — the DeMo/DisTrO work draws on signal processing (DCT compression) and distributed systems concepts where his background is relevant. He has appeared on the a16z AI podcast alongside Nous co-founder Bowen Peng to discuss DisTrO and their mission to accelerate open-source AI research.\n\n**Karan Malhotra — Co-founder & Head of Behavior**\n\nMalhotra oversees the behavioral alignment and data synthesis strategies that define the Hermes model family. His background is unconventional — studying Religion and Philosophy at Emory University before working as a Machine Learning Researcher at the Stanford Brain Stimulation Lab. He has been the primary public spokesperson for Nous, telling Fortune, "We don't want to get kind of bogged down by the traditional view of how crypto operates when we're a very serious research lab and an academic lab." Malhotra described Nous's founding team as "crypto native," though they were hesitant about adding a blockchain element before their research breakthrough.\n\n**Teknium (Ryan) — Co-founder & Head of Post Training**\n\nTeknium is the creator of the Hermes model family and leads all post-training efforts. He led the fine-tuning process and dataset curation for the original Hermes models. With significant social media following, he is one of the most influential voices in the open-source AI community. His technical contributions include the OpenHermes datasets and DataForge synthetic data generation system.\n\n**Shivani Mitra — Co-founder**\n\nLimited public information is available about Mitra's specific role. Notably, Shivani Mitra is listed as an angel investor in Prime Intellect's seed round, suggesting she maintains relationships across the decentralized AI ecosystem.\n\n**Bowen Peng — Co-founder**\n\nBowen Peng is a cofounder of Nous Research and co-author of the DeMo paper (alongside Jeffrey Quesnelle and Diederik Kingma). He appears to be a primary research contributor but maintains a lower public profile.\n\n### Paradigm (Lead Series A Investor)\n\nFounded by Coinbase's Fred Ehrsam and Sequoia's Matt Huang, Paradigm is one of the largest crypto-native venture firms, with a new fund of $850 million closed last year. Web3 data platform Kaito AI ranked Paradigm as the top-performing crypto VC over the past year, posting an impressive 11.80% performance metric.\n\nThe depth of Paradigm's involvement appears to be primarily financial. Paradigm partner Arjun Balaji stated: "This open, community-oriented approach is a powerful contrast to the closed, centralized efforts from incumbent labs." This is not Paradigm's first foray into the sector, having previously led an $18 million Series A round for decentralized AI training platform Vana. Paradigm's involvement signals serious crypto-investor conviction but does not bring AI-specific distribution or technical expertise.\n\n### Andreessen Horowitz (Grant)\n\nNous Research also received a grant from Andreessen Horowitz at some point, according to a LinkedIn post. The a16z relationship is notable — Nous founders appeared on the a16z AI podcast, and a16z partner Anjney Midha (who also sits on the board of Mistral AI and Black Forest Labs) has shown interest. However, the relationship is through a grant, not an equity investment, which typically indicates a lighter-touch engagement.\n\n### Build-in-Public / Community Signals\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|--------|-------|\n| Twitter Followers (@NousResearch) | ~83,300 |\n| HuggingFace Downloads (Hermes 3+) | 50M+ (per Delphi Ventures) |\n| Discord | Active (link on site; used as primary community hub) |\n| GitHub Repos | Multiple active repos (Atropos, DisTrO, Psyche) |\n| LinkedIn Followers | ~1,100 |\n| Team Size | ~20 |\n\nAll core components of Nous's AI stack — including their Hermes language models, datasets, and training methods — are fully open-source and publicly available. Quesnelle emphasized this is more than open weights: it includes publishing breakthrough research in academic journals and fostering a worldwide, collaborative Discord community.\n\n---\n\n## Token Economics\n\n### NOUS Token Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| Token | $NOUS (anticipated) |\n| Chain | Solana |\n| Token Status | **Not yet launched** |\n| Series A Valuation | $1B (token valuation) |\n| Total Raised | ~$70M |\n| Token Use Cases | Governance, compute rewards, staking (planned) |\n| Tokenomics | **Not yet published** |\n\nAs of now, Nous Research has not officially launched the NOUS token. Therefore, all price predictions are speculative and based on future potential rather than current market data. Nous has not yet released a tokenomics schedule for their project.\n\n### Value Flow Analysis\n\nThe intended token value flow, based on available information:\n\n1. **Compute Contributors** → Provide GPU resources to Psyche Network\n2. **Coordinators** → Track contributions and assign points via on-chain smart contracts\n3. Coordinators track client contributions and assign a points-based system to verify work. These points would then be redeemed for Nous tokens via a treasurer smart contract.\n4. **Token Holders** → Anticipated governance rights over the network\n\nMalhotra said Nous is still deciding whether users will be rewarded with a proprietary token created by the startup or Solana's native cryptocurrency. This indecision as of April 2025 — despite a $1B token valuation — is a notable risk factor. The valuation is based on a token that does not yet exist, with economics that have not been finalized.\n\n### Staking Mechanics\n\nNot publicly available. No staking program has been announced. Any referenced APY or reward mechanisms are entirely forward-looking.\n\n---\n\n## Competitive Landscape\n\n### Decentralized AI Training Competitors\n\n| Company | Founded | Funding | Chain | Key Tech | Status |\n|---------|---------|---------|-------|----------|--------|\n| **Nous Research** | 2022 | $70M | Solana | DeMo/DisTrO | Testnet live; Consilience 40B trained |\n| **Gensyn** | 2020 | $50.6M | Ethereum Rollup | Consistent ML execution, trustless verification, P2P communication | Public Testnet launched March 2025 |\n| **Prime Intellect** | 2023 | $70.4M | Protocol TBD | DiLoCo/PRIME-RL | Demonstrated 10B-parameter model across 14 nodes spanning three continents; released INTELLECT-3, a 106B MoE model |\n| **Pluralis Research** | 2024 | $7.6M seed | TBD | Asynchronous model parallelism | Early stage |\n| **Bittensor** | 2019 | N/A (token live) | Polkadot | Subnet-based incentive network | Live mainnet |\n\nCompared with decentralized training projects such as Gensyn, Prime Intellect, Nous Research, and Pluralis, each focuses on different aspects of the stack. Gensyn focuses on verifiable execution and trustless coordination. Prime Intellect provides an all-in-one compute marketplace plus distributed training. Nous's differentiation is the combination of (a) a proven model-building track record (Hermes), (b) a novel optimizer (DeMo/DisTrO), and (c) Solana-based coordination.\n\n### Open-Source Model Builders\n\nNous also competes in the open-source LLM space against:\n\n- **Meta AI (Llama):** The dominant open-source base model provider. Nous fine-tunes on top of Llama.\n- **Mistral AI:** French lab with similar open-source ethos but different business model (enterprise API).\n- **DeepSeek:** Chinese lab producing competitive open-weight models (V3, R1).\n- **Alibaba (Qwen):** NousCoder-14B is built on Qwen3-14B, demonstrating the interdependency.\n\n### Competitive Advantages\n\n- **Proven model quality:** Hermes 3 has surpassed 50 million downloads, demonstrating genuine community adoption rather than speculative interest.\n- **Peer-reviewed research:** The DeMo paper has been accepted to ICLR 2026, providing academic credibility rare among crypto-AI projects.\n- **Operational proof:** The Psyche-trained version of Hermes 4.3 outperformed the traditional centralized version, confirming that Psyche is up to the task of training production models.\n- **Strong community DNA:** Founded in 2022 by a group of open-source researchers who met on platforms like Discord, GitHub, and Twitter.\n- **Collaboration with credible researchers:** Nous collaborated with Diederik P. Kingma, a member of the OpenAI founding team, on the DeMo research.\n\n### Competitive Risks\n\n- **Scale gap:** Even the largest decentralized models (including Nous' Consilience 40B) have been trained with 1,000x less compute than today's frontier models. This is a fundamental barrier to competing at the frontier.\n- **Fast-moving competitors:** Prime Intellect has already raised similar total funding ($70.4M) and released INTELLECT-3, a 106B MoE model, showing rapid competitive escalation.\n- **Dependency on base models:** Hermes models are fine-tunes of Meta's Llama and other base models, creating platform dependency.\n- **Token economics uncertainty:** The $1B valuation is based on an unlaunched token with undefined economics — a significant speculative premium.\n\n---\n\n## Key Metrics & Traction\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|--------|-------|--------|\n| Total Funding | ~$70M | Multiple (Fortune, The Block) |\n| Series A Valuation | $1B (token valuation) | Fortune (April 2025) |\n| Team Size | ~20 | Fortune, PitchBook |\n| Hermes Downloads (Total) | 50M+ | Delphi Ventures (self-reported via investor) |\n| Twitter Followers | ~83,300 | X.com |\n| DeMo Paper | Accepted at ICLR 2026 | Nous Research (X post, Feb 2026) |\n| Consilience 40B | Largest internet pre-training run | Nous Research (self-reported) |\n| Hermes 4 405B MATH-500 | 96.3% | VentureBeat (self-reported benchmarks) |\n| Hermes 4 405B AIME'24 | 81.9% | VentureBeat (self-reported benchmarks) |\n| NousCoder-14B LiveCodeBench v6 | 67.87% Pass@1 | Nous Research |\n| Hermes 4.3 Psyche Training | 144k tokens/sec across 24 nodes | Nous Research |\n| Psyche Testnet GPU Donations | $500K in 44 minutes | AIbase |\n| HQ | Austin, TX (600 Congress Ave) | PitchBook |\n\nThe 50M+ download figure for Hermes is an exceptionally strong signal for a ~20-person lab. For context, this puts Nous's models among the most widely adopted open-source fine-tunes on HuggingFace. The benchmark results for Hermes 4 are self-reported; while the company has published evaluation outputs for transparency, independent verification is limited. Nous acknowledges that standard benchmarks "are easily gamed."\n\nWithin 44 minutes of launching the testnet, the project raised $500,000 worth of GPU power through donations, reflecting extraordinary community enthusiasm for Psyche. However, donation-driven testnet participation may not translate into sustained economic participation at mainnet scale.\n\n---\n\n## Risk Analysis\n\n### Platform/Dependency Risk\n\nNous Research's model-building practice has a fundamental dependency on upstream base model providers. The Hermes series is fine-tuned on Meta's Llama models, and NousCoder-14B is built on Alibaba's Qwen3. If Meta restricts future Llama releases (which has been a concern — Quesnelle himself raised this concern: "What if we don't get Llama 4? That's like an actual existential threat because the closed providers will continue to get better and we would be dead in the water."), Nous's post-training business would be severely impacted. Consilience 40B represents a move toward training from scratch, but this is an order of magnitude more expensive and computationally demanding. The dependency on Solana for Psyche coordination also introduces blockchain-specific risks (network outages, fee spikes, regulatory pressure on Solana).\n\n### Regulatory Risk\n\nDecentralized AI training sits in a complex regulatory gray area. Distributed training creates fragmented jurisdictional risks around data privacy. Many proposals for monitoring and regulating AI depend on internet decentralized training continuing to lag far behind the frontier. If regulators view decentralized training as a mechanism for evading compute governance regimes (which some policymakers are actively developing), Nous could face direct regulatory headwinds. The "uncensored" positioning of Hermes models, while appealing to the open-source community, could also attract regulatory scrutiny — particularly if models are used for harmful purposes. The crypto/token dimension adds securities law complexity on top of AI-specific regulation.\n\n### Team Execution Risk\n\nNous currently has a 20-odd-person team, with much of the new funding going to compute power and expanding research capabilities. Building and operating a decentralized training network while simultaneously maintaining one of the most popular open-source model families and shipping new products (Hermes Agent, NousCoder, Atropos) is extremely ambitious for a team of this size. The founding team's backgrounds are diverse but not traditional AI research (Quesnelle comes from automotive systems/MEV, Malhotra from philosophy/religion). While this has not prevented impressive results so far, scaling to compete with labs like Mistral (~800 employees) or well-funded competitors like Prime Intellect will require significant team growth and potentially a cultural shift from research collective to commercial organization.\n\n### Token/Dilution Risk\n\nThe $1 billion valuation is a token valuation — not an equity valuation — for a token that does not yet exist. Nous Research has not officially launched the NOUS token. Nous has not yet released a tokenomics schedule for their project. This means investors are pricing future token economics without knowing allocation percentages, vesting schedules, or even whether the token will be used (vs. SOL). The history of crypto-AI projects launching tokens at high FDVs and seeing significant post-launch dilution is well-documented. Until the tokenomics are published, the $1B valuation should be treated as highly uncertain.\n\n### Market Sizing Reality Check\n\nThe decentralized AI training market is real but nascent. The decentralized AI compute marketplace has seen rapid growth in 2025, valued at $12.2 billion in 2024 and expected to reach $39.5 billion by 2033. However, the critical question is whether decentralized training can actually produce frontier-competitive models. In practice, training decentrally over the internet has lagged far behind more centralized training. Even the largest decentralized models have been trained with 1,000x less compute than today's frontier models. If this gap persists, the addressable market for decentralized training may be limited to non-frontier applications — still valuable, but a different investment thesis than "competing with OpenAI."\n\n---\n\n## Investment Considerations\n\n### Bull Case\n\n- **Genuine research moat:** The DeMo paper's acceptance at ICLR 2026 is not vaporware — it represents peer-reviewed fundamental research in communication-efficient optimization. This is the rare crypto-AI project with credible academic validation.\n- **Proven product-market fit for models:** 50M+ downloads of Hermes models demonstrate that Nous has built something people actually want to use, independent of any token or blockchain narrative. The model brand has standalone value.\n- **Psyche validation milestone:** The Psyche-trained Hermes 4.3 outperforming the centralized version is potentially a watershed moment — if decentralized training produces *better* models (due to diversity of compute, data, or other factors), it fundamentally changes the economic equation.\n- **Paradigm backing at an inflection point:** Paradigm is the highest-signal investor in crypto. Their $50M bet — essentially their conviction investment for the crypto-AI thesis — provides significant follow-on capital signaling power and ecosystem access.\n- **Macro timing:** Growing skepticism of closed-source AI monopolies, rising compute costs, and the open-source AI movement's momentum all create tailwinds for Nous's positioning.\n\n### Bear Case\n\n- **1,000x compute gap to frontier:** The largest decentralized models have been trained with 1,000x less compute than today's frontier models. Closing this gap requires not just better algorithms but also massive capital investment in GPU hardware — which a decentralized network may struggle to coordinate.\n- **Undefined token economics at $1B valuation:** Investing at a $1B token valuation for a token whose allocation, supply, vesting, and utility are all undefined represents extraordinary speculative risk. If the token launches with unfavorable economics (high insider allocation, rapid unlocks), early investors could see significant dilution.\n- **Team scale mismatch:** A 20-person team is attempting to simultaneously (a) run a cutting-edge AI research lab, (b) build and operate a blockchain-based distributed compute network, (c) develop consumer products (Nous Chat), and (d) maintain open-source community engagement. Each of these is a full-company effort for most organizations. Something will inevitably receive insufficient attention.\n- **Revenue model remains theoretical:** There is no publicly disclosed revenue. The API, chat product, and token are all either nascent or not yet launched. The $70M in funding is being consumed primarily by compute costs, which creates a ticking clock for demonstrating commercial viability.\n- **Competitive intensity:** Prime Intellect has raised equivalent funding ($70.4M) and already trained a 106B-parameter model. Gensyn has a16z backing and a different but equally credible technical approach. The decentralized AI training space is becoming crowded, and first-mover advantages in crypto-AI are historically fragile.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nNous Research represents one of the most technically credible projects at the intersection of open-source AI and blockchain infrastructure. Unlike the vast majority of crypto-AI projects, Nous has demonstrated genuine research contributions (ICLR-accepted DeMo paper), shipped widely-adopted products (50M+ Hermes downloads), and proven that its decentralized training infrastructure can produce production-quality models (Hermes 4.3 on Psyche). The founding team's unconventional backgrounds — blending crypto-native engineering, philosophy, and practical AI fine-tuning expertise — have proven surprisingly effective at navigating both the AI research and crypto communities.\n\nHowever, the investment carries meaningful risks. The $1B token valuation is anchored to a token that does not yet exist, with unpublished economics. The 1,000x compute gap between decentralized and frontier training remains a sobering reality check on the "competing with OpenAI" narrative. And the team's ability to scale from a 20-person research collective to a fully commercial operation — while maintaining the open-source ethos that drives community support — remains unproven.\n\n### Key Open Questions for Further Diligence\n\n- **Tokenomics timeline and structure:** When will the NOUS token launch, and what will the allocation be between team, investors, community, and compute contributors? What percentage unlocks at TGE?\n- **Revenue projections:** What is the current run-rate for API revenue through Nous Portal? What is the planned commercial model for Psyche mainnet?\n- **Compute economics validation:** Can Nous provide verified cost-per-token comparisons between Psyche-trained and centrally-trained models at equivalent quality?\n- **Team scaling plan:** What is the hiring roadmap, and how will the team grow from 20 to the scale needed to operate both a research lab and a production network?\n- **Base model dependency strategy:** As Consilience progresses, what is the roadmap for reducing dependence on Meta/Llama and other upstream base models?\n\n### Key Metric to Watch\n\nThe single most important metric going forward is **Psyche mainnet launch and sustained compute participation** — specifically, the number of active GPU nodes, aggregate throughput, and the quality of models trained on the network at scale. If Psyche can demonstrate that decentralized training consistently produces competitive models at lower cost, the entire thesis validates. If compute participation plateaus or model quality degrades at scale, the infrastructure thesis weakens regardless of Hermes model adoption.	complete	2026-03-11 05:28:29.172463
507b4ed9-befc-4809-bec0-e64ec2753f70	1b06af05-1b8d-4312-8cd4-b0de8fad4245	1e9bf641-c93c-4629-906a-f50db9050164	Covenant AI (Templar) — Deep Research Report	# Covenant AI (Templar) — Deep Research Report\n\n**Decentralized AI training infrastructure on Bittensor, enabling permissionless, incentivized pre-training, post-training, and compute provisioning for large language models.**\n\n**Website:** https://tplr.ai\n\n**Built by Covenant AI (Samuel Dare, team) | Operates on Bittensor (Subnet 3, 39, 81) | No confirmed external VC backers**\n\n---\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nCovenant AI is building an end-to-end decentralized AI training stack on the Bittensor blockchain, consisting of three interconnected platforms ("orders"): Templar (decentralized pre-training), Basilica (decentralized compute), and Grail (decentralized post-training). The project's core technical achievement is Covenant72B — the largest model trained on decentralized infrastructure (72B parameters), trained on approximately 1.1–1.2 trillion tokens across commodity internet links with permissionless participation. The project has published a formal technical report on arXiv, and its benchmark results show the model is substantially larger in scale than existing training runs over globally distributed compute and far exceeds the performance of prior decentralized models, achieving stronger performance in ARC-Challenge, MMLU, and ARC-Easy than K2, and exceeding or on par with LLaMA-2-70B.\n\nThe core thesis is that decentralized AI training can become competitive with centralized alternatives, breaking the monopoly of hyperscaler-controlled AI development. This matters now because the cost and concentration of AI compute is reaching untenable levels, and decentralized approaches that can match centralized performance would fundamentally alter the economics of model training. For the first time, there's a credible technical path toward intelligence developed as genuinely distributed public infrastructure rather than a corporate-controlled product.\n\nCovenant AI has no confirmed traditional VC funding — it operates entirely on Bittensor's TAO emission system. Two Covenant AI papers have been accepted at NeurIPS OPT2025, marking the first time research from Bittensor has been accepted at a major ML conference. The project is transitioning from pure research to a research-plus-product model, with training/fine-tune APIs, enterprise sales already in motion, and a longer-term aim to release a competitive base model and vertically integrated stack. A key upcoming catalyst is the "Templar: Crusades" competition system, with multi-GPU Crusades going live in early March 2026.\n\n---\n\n## Product Overview\n\n### Core Product\n\nCovenant AI operates three interconnected subnets ("orders") on the Bittensor network, each addressing a different component of the AI training pipeline:\n\n| Order | Subnet | Function | Status |\n|-------|--------|----------|--------|\n| Templar | Subnet 3 | Permissionless decentralized LLM pre-training | ✅ Live (Covenant72B complete) |\n| Basilica | Subnet 39 | Decentralized GPU compute provisioning | ⏳ In development |\n| Grail | Subnet 81 | Reinforcement learning-based post-training | ⏳ In development |\n\n**Templar (Subnet 3)** is the flagship product. τemplar is a decentralized training framework that enables large-scale model training across heterogeneous compute resources over the internet. By connecting diverse computational nodes through a carefully designed incentive mechanism, τemplar makes it possible to train large models collaboratively while ensuring honest participation and quality contributions.\n\nThe user flow works as follows: Miners start by synchronizing their model with the latest global state. They attempt to load the latest model checkpoint from the validator with the highest stake. If no checkpoint is available, they initialize their model from scratch. Each miner retrieves a specific subset of the dataset for the current window. The data assignment is deterministic, based on a seed derived from the miner's UID and the window number. This ensures that miners have unique but consistent data assignments per window.\n\nThe system uses an asynchronous model. Miners train the model on assigned data subsets and share their gradients with peers. They load a subset of the dataset based on the current window and their UID, perform forward and backward passes to compute gradients, and compress gradients using DCT transform and top-k selection. Validators then evaluate gradient quality by measuring loss improvement and update OpenSkill ratings accordingly.\n\n**Basilica (Subnet 39)** is positioned as a decentralized compute marketplace. Basilica is positioned as a compute network that will evolve beyond "rentals" into value-added services like verifiable inference and hardware-efficiency tricks to cut the "Jensen tax." The vision is to create a permissionless, community-owned compute cloud.\n\n**Grail (Subnet 81)** targets single- then multi-turn RL, plus a fast hidden-state "fingerprint" to verify miners' outputs and model usage.\n\n### Core Technical Innovations\n\nCovenant AI's technical differentiation rests on two peer-reviewed algorithms:\n\n**SparseLoCo** — a communication-efficient optimizer that combines top-k sparsification with 2-bit quantization. SparseLoCo compresses gradients to 0.78% of their original size while allowing nodes to take many local training steps before synchronizing. Training a 72-billion-parameter model went from requiring 280GB per sync to 2.2GB per sync, while synchronizing 500x less frequently. This directly addresses the primary bottleneck in decentralized training: communication overhead.\n\n**Gauntlet** — a blockchain-compatible reward mechanism for allocating incentives and encouraging honest participation. The system uses gradient evaluation where validators compute a score based on loss improvement from each miner's gradient, OpenSkill ratings where miners are rated using the PlackettLuce model based on their contributions, and weight setting on the blockchain based on these ratings.\n\n### Asset Universe / Scope\n\nThe primary "asset" Covenant AI produces is open-source language models trained on decentralized infrastructure. The flagship model, Covenant72B, uses a LLaMA-style architecture. The model architecture is LLaMA-style, trained on 1.2 trillion tokens. More than twenty participants around the world contribute GPU power. Network overhead remains low at six percent.\n\nA chat interface is available at tplr.ai/chat, allowing users to chat with Covenant 72B — a 72B parameter large language model trained on Bittensor's decentralized Templar network.\n\n### UX, Tooling & Technical Architecture\n\nThe architecture is built around several key components:\n\n- **R2 Storage (Cloudflare):** Used for gradient upload/download between miners and validators, enabling asynchronous communication\n- **Bittensor Chain:** On-chain weight setting and reward distribution via Yuma Consensus\n- **DCT Transform + Top-K Selection:** Gradient compression pipeline that dramatically reduces bandwidth\n- **OpenSkill Rating System (PlackettLuce model):** Statistical model for ranking miner contributions fairly\n- **Deterministic Data Assignment:** Seed-based system preventing miners from manipulating their datasets\n- **Asynchronous Python (asyncio):** The implementation follows an asynchronous model, with extensive use of Python's asyncio for handling concurrent operations\n\nThe entire codebase is open source on GitHub (github.com/tplr-ai/templar and github.com/one-covenant/templar).\n\n### Additional Products / Roadmap\n\n| Feature | Status |\n|---------|--------|\n| Templar pre-training framework | ✅ Live |\n| Covenant72B training run | ✅ Complete |\n| Covenant72B technical report (arXiv) | ✅ Published (March 2026) |\n| Covenant72B Chat (SFT version) | ✅ Live |\n| NeurIPS OPT2025 papers (Gauntlet, SparseLoCo) | ✅ Accepted |\n| Templar: Crusades (MFU competition) | ✅ Multi-GPU live (March 2026) |\n| Heterogeneous SparseLoCo | ⏳ Research published, not yet production |\n| Training/fine-tuning APIs | ⏳ In development |\n| Enterprise sales | ⏳ In motion (no public details) |\n| Basilica compute marketplace | ⏳ In development |\n| Grail post-training/RL | ⏳ In development |\n| Unified Covenant token economics | ⏳ Planned, no ship date |\n\n**Templar: Crusades** is a noteworthy development. The team is finalizing Templar: Crusades, a competition system where you submit training code, we evaluate it on target hardware, and the fastest implementation earns emissions. The Crusades MFU (Model FLOPs Utilization) competition has already shown results — the Crusades MFU competition hit 66% on single A100, up from 30% during the training run. This is significant because it means the community is more than doubling training efficiency through competitive optimization.\n\n**Heterogeneous SparseLoCo** is an important research milestone but is published research, not yet production deployment. Templar currently runs SparseLoCo in production for Covenant72B training. Integrating heterogeneous capabilities requires additional engineering, testing, and likely several iterations to discover edge cases that didn't appear in controlled experiments. This would enable consumer-grade GPUs to participate alongside datacenter hardware, dramatically expanding the potential miner base.\n\n---\n\n## Business Model & Economics\n\n### Revenue Streams\n\nCovenant AI currently has **no live revenue streams** — it operates entirely on Bittensor's TAO emission system. The planned revenue model involves:\n\n1. **Paid Pre-Training Services:** Templar is planning to offer pre-training services for niche foundation models. Clients would pay to have custom models trained on Covenant's decentralized infrastructure.\n\n2. **Training/Fine-Tuning APIs:** Sam outlines a shift from pure research to research-plus-product: training/fine-tune APIs, enterprise sales already in motion.\n\n3. **Token Buyback from Fees:** 100% of training fees will buy back Covenant tokens. This creates a direct value flow from product revenue to token holders, though the mechanism requires live revenue to be meaningful.\n\n4. **TAO Emissions:** Currently the primary source of economic value. Templar is currently in a 100% burn period. Miners are not being evaluated and no emissions are being distributed. This is a critical point — the subnet is currently in a transitional period between the completed 72B run and the next phase (Crusades).\n\n### On-Chain / Technical Execution Model\n\nThe project operates within Bittensor's substrate-based blockchain architecture. Under the Dynamic TAO (dTAO) system introduced in February 2025, Bittensor introduced alpha tokens for each subnet, allowing market participants to directly stake in subnets they believe in. A subnet's share of TAO emissions is now determined by market-driven demand for its alpha token.\n\nTemplar's alpha token (γ) trades on Bittensor's AMM. Based on recent subnet data, Subnet 3 (templar) has a price of approximately 0.02 τ/γ and a market cap of approximately τ 57.32. At current TAO prices (~$210), this implies a subnet market cap of approximately $12,000 — extremely early-stage and thin.\n\nOne analysis placed Templar at a current market value of 35M, accounting for 4.79% of emissions (this figure likely from mid-2025 and may not reflect the current burn period).\n\n### Unit Economics\n\nThe economics of decentralized training are fundamentally different from centralized approaches:\n\n- **Cost advantage:** Decentralized training eliminates the need for massive datacenter capital expenditure. However, it introduces communication overhead and coordination costs.\n- **Communication efficiency:** SparseLoCo reduced communication overhead to ~6%, meaning ~94% of compute time is productive training.\n- **Miner economics:** Miners require high-end GPUs. Joining is open, but competitiveness still requires high-end GPUs such as 8×B200 setups. This limits the effective "permissionless" claim somewhat — while anyone can join, only those with significant GPU hardware can compete meaningfully.\n- **Performance gap:** Sam pegs the Covenant72B model at ~60% of top SOTA today. While impressive for decentralized training, this means the models are not yet commercially competitive with frontier centralized models.\n\n---\n\n## Team & Backers\n\n### Samuel Dare (Founder)\n\nSamuel Dare brings over eight years of blockchain experience. His background spans multiple roles:\n\n- **Akropolis (CTO):** At Brave Software, he championed Blockchain and DeFi Integrations, working to channel Brave's 22 Million MAU into DeFi. The Akropolis Substack confirms his CTO role at this DeFi protocol. Notably, Akropolis suffered a $2 million loss following a re-entrancy attack in November 2020, though this occurred while the project was operational rather than being attributable to a specific team member.\n\n- **Khalani (Co-founder):** The deal card lists Dare as a co-founder. However, according to Tracxn, the founders of Khalani Network are Kevin Wang and Tannr Allard, founded in 2023. The Khalani blog also mentions "Tannr and Kevin" as founders. **This is a discrepancy that warrants further diligence.** Dare may have been involved in an early capacity but is not listed as a founder in public records.\n\n- **Shell (Technical Lead - Blockchain):** Confirmed via LinkedIn.\n- **Brave Software (Blockchain Architect):** At Brave Software, he championed Blockchain and DeFi Integrations.\n- **Oxford Saïd Business School:** Education confirmed via deal card.\n\nDare's background is notably **deep in blockchain but light in ML/AI research**. Sam's journey into the world of blockchain, from nightclub promoter to DeFi CTO, adds a personal touch. This is a meaningful domain gap — leading a decentralized AI training project requires deep ML expertise that Dare has apparently built through this project rather than bringing from prior experience.\n\n### Evangelos Pappas (Co-founder)\n\nPappas serves as both a strategic leader and hands-on developer across the three subnets. His background spans blockchain engineering. Limited independent information is publicly available about his specific prior work history.\n\n### Joel Lidin (AI Researcher & Engineer)\n\nLidin contributes to ML research efforts. The MMLU curve showing Covenant's first reasoning breakthrough beyond random chance was attributed to Joel Lidin (October 2025). His AI research background complements the blockchain expertise of the other team members.\n\n### Backing & Funding\n\n**There are no confirmed external VC investors.** This is both a strength and a weakness:\n\n- **Strength:** The project has been entirely bootstrapped through Bittensor's emission system, proving that the incentive model can sustain serious R&D without traditional venture capital.\n- **Weakness:** The project lacks the capital runway that competitors have. Prime Intellect has raised $20.5M, Nous Research has raised $70M+, and Gensyn has raised $50.6M.\n\nThe project operates under the Bittensor ecosystem umbrella, where Polychain held around $200 million of TAO, Dao5 held $50 million, and Digital Currency Group had around $100 million. These are backers of the broader Bittensor ecosystem, not of Covenant AI specifically.\n\n### Build-in-Public / Community Signals\n\n- **Twitter (@tplr_ai):** Active account with regular updates; the Covenant72B announcement received 1.2 million views\n- **Weekly TGIF updates:** Regular public communication through Twitter Spaces and video streams\n- **Substack (Templar Research Blog):** Technical updates published periodically\n- **GitHub:** Fully open-source codebase\n- **Podcast appearances:** Multiple appearances on Bittensor ecosystem podcasts (Chain of Thought, Hash Rate, Novelty Search, Ventura Labs)\n- **Covenant72B technical report:** Published on arXiv in March 2026, demonstrating research transparency\n\n---\n\n## Token Economics\n\n### Bittensor Subnet Token Parameters\n\nCovenant AI does not have its own standalone token. It operates within Bittensor's dTAO system:\n\n| Parameter | Details |\n|-----------|---------|\n| Parent Token | $TAO (Bittensor) |\n| Subnet Token | γ (gamma) — Templar Subnet 3 alpha token |\n| Token Supply Cap | 21M γ (same as TAO) |\n| Token Launch | dTAO launch (February 2025) |\n| Current Price | ~0.02 τ/γ |\n| Emission Model | Flow-based (net TAO staking determines emissions) |\n| Halving Schedule | Mirrors Bitcoin/TAO schedule |\n| Planned Sovereign Token | Hinted ("Covenant tokens") but not yet launched |\n\n### Token Distribution & Value Flow\n\nUnder Bittensor's current system, 41% of emissions go to miners, with allocation to particular miners determined by Yuma Consensus. Validators and subnet owners receive additional portions.\n\nThe planned value flow is: **Paid training fees → 100% used to buy back Covenant tokens → value accrual to token holders**. However, this requires three things that don't yet exist: (1) live revenue from training services, (2) a Covenant-specific token, and (3) the buyback mechanism itself. Sam hints at unifying token economics across the three "orders", but details are sparse.\n\n**Critical note:** Token economics are evolving, and long-term sustainability is untested. Currently, the subnet is in a 100% burn period with no emissions being distributed, making any token-based valuation extremely speculative.\n\n### Staking Mechanics\n\nTAO holders can stake into Subnet 3 by purchasing γ tokens through Bittensor's AMM. As TAO-holders stake TAO into subnets in exchange for the subnet-specific alpha, they are essentially 'voting with their TAO' for the value of the subnet. Subnets with more staking than unstaking receive higher emissions, while subnets with net outflows receive reduced or zero emissions. This flow-based model rewards subnets that attract genuine user engagement.\n\n---\n\n## Competitive Landscape\n\n### Traditional / Established Competitors\n\n| Project | Funding | Model | Key Differentiator | Training Approach |\n|---------|---------|-------|-------|----------|\n| **OpenAI** | $20B+ | GPT-4o, o1 | Frontier performance | Centralized |\n| **Anthropic** | $15B+ | Claude 3.5 | Safety-focused | Centralized |\n| **Meta** | Internal | LLaMA 3.1 | Open weights | Centralized |\n| **DeepSeek** | Internal | R1-0528 | Cost efficiency | Centralized |\n\nCovenant AI is not competing directly with these labs today. Sam pegs the Covenant72B at ~60% of top SOTA today. The competitive positioning is about building the infrastructure for a future where decentralized training *could* rival centralized labs.\n\n### Crypto-Native / Direct Competitors\n\n| Project | Funding | Key Model | Blockchain | Decentralized Training? | Status |\n|---------|---------|-----------|------------|------------------------|--------|\n| **Prime Intellect** | $20.5M total | INTELLECT-3 (106B MoE) | Ethereum-based protocol | Raised $20M promising decentralized AI training. Its flagship model trained on a centralized 512-GPU cluster instead. | Live (centralized RL) |\n| **Nous Research** | $50M Series A from Paradigm at $1B token valuation | Hermes 3 | Solana | Actively building, no timeline for when it will go live | Pre-production |\n| **Gensyn** | $50.6M total from a16z, Galaxy, others | N/A (compute marketplace) | Ethereum L2 | Testnet only | Testnet |\n| **IOTA Subnet** | TAO emissions | N/A | Bittensor | Pipeline parallelism approach | Experimental |\n| **Pluralis.ai** | Unknown | N/A | Unknown | SWARM parallelism | Research |\n\n### Competitive Advantages\n\n- **First and only fully permissionless, live production system** for decentralized training at the 72B parameter scale. Covenant-72B is substantially larger in scale than existing training runs over globally distributed compute. No competitor has achieved this.\n\n- **Peer-reviewed research** with two NeurIPS workshop papers. This marks the first time research from Bittensor has been accepted at a major ML conference. This gives academic credibility that other Bittensor subnets lack.\n\n- **Vertically integrated stack** covering pre-training (Templar), compute (Basilica), and post-training (Grail), compared to competitors that focus on single layers.\n\n- **Truly permissionless** — unlike Prime Intellect, which trained its flagship model on a centralized 512-GPU cluster despite its decentralized AI mission. Covenant AI's training run had no whitelist and anyone with GPUs could freely join or leave.\n\n- **Zero external capital dependency** — the project has proven it can produce real output without VC funding, while competitors have spent $50-70M+ without shipping comparable decentralized training capabilities.\n\n### Competitive Risks\n\n- **Massive funding asymmetry:** Competitors have $20-70M+ in VC capital; Covenant has zero external funding. This limits hiring, compute procurement, and marketing capacity.\n\n- **Model quality gap:** 60% of SOTA is impressive for a proof of concept but not commercially viable. Competitors like Prime Intellect are achieving state-of-the-art results (via centralized training) while building decentralized infrastructure in parallel.\n\n- **Nous Research's brand and distribution:** Hermes 3 has surpassed 50 million downloads, giving Nous a massive distribution advantage if they ship decentralized training.\n\n- **Gensyn's institutional backing:** With a $43 million Series A round led by a16z and a Layer-1 approach, Gensyn has enterprise credibility that a Bittensor subnet may lack.\n\n- **Bittensor ecosystem dependency:** Covenant's success is partly contingent on the broader Bittensor ecosystem thriving — a risk outside their control.\n\n---\n\n## Key Metrics & Traction\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|--------|-------|--------|\n| Model Parameters | 72 billion | Confirmed (arXiv report) |\n| Training Tokens | ~1.1-1.2 trillion | Confirmed (multiple sources) |\n| Communication Overhead | ~6% | Confirmed (multiple sources) |\n| Gradient Compression | 0.78% of original size | Confirmed (technical report) |\n| Active Miners (during run) | ~20+ globally distributed | Confirmed |\n| Crusades MFU (single A100) | 66% (up from 30%) | Self-reported |\n| Twitter Announcement Views | 1.2 million | Self-reported |\n| NeurIPS Workshop Papers | 2 (OPT2025) | Confirmed |\n| External VC Funding | $0 | Confirmed |\n| Subnet Market Cap (approx.) | Variable (currently in burn period) | On-chain data |\n| TAO Price | ~$210 (as of March 2026) | CoinGecko |\n| Bittensor FDV | ~$4.4B | CoinGecko |\n\nThe Covenant72B technical report confirms benchmark results: stronger performance in ARC-Challenge, MMLU, and ARC-Easy than K2, and exceeding or on par with LLaMA-2-70B. We observe slightly lower performance across HellaSwag, OpenBookQA, and WinoGrande than K2 and LLaMA-2-70B, which were trained on larger token budgets.\n\nContext: These benchmark comparisons are against models from 2023 (LLaMA-2-70B) and an earlier open-source training effort (K2). They do not compare favorably to 2025-era frontier models. However, for a fully decentralized, permissionless training run, these results represent a genuinely unprecedented achievement. The key comparison is not against centralized frontier labs but against other decentralized training attempts, where Covenant72B stands alone.\n\n---\n\n## Risk Analysis\n\n### Platform/Dependency Risk\n\nCovenant AI is entirely dependent on the Bittensor network. If Bittensor's protocol faces technical issues, governance failures, or economic collapse, Covenant would be severely impacted. Since its mainnet launch in January 2021, Bittensor has faced a range of challenges, including incentive misalignments, centralization concerns, weight-copying among validators, memetic subnet exploitation, a malicious PyPI package attack, and the "runaway batch call" overload incident in May 2025. While these have been addressed incrementally, the Bittensor network remains experimental infrastructure. Additionally, the dTAO emission model is subject to gaming — the market-based mechanism introduced vulnerabilities, with some subnets exploiting the model by encouraging holders to buy alpha tokens to inflate prices and secure disproportionate TAO emissions without contributing meaningful work. Covenant's legitimate contributions could be undermined by ecosystem-level manipulation.\n\n### Regulatory Risk\n\nDecentralized AI training sits in a regulatory gray zone. On one hand, the EU AI Act and similar frameworks are focused on model deployers and high-risk applications rather than training infrastructure. On the other hand, permissionless training where "anyone with GPUs could join" creates audit and compliance challenges. If regulators require training provenance, data curation transparency, or compute attribution, Covenant's permissionless model could face friction. Additionally, the token economics (TAO emissions, potential Covenant token) face evolving securities regulation globally.\n\n### Team Execution Risk\n\nThe founder's background is in blockchain infrastructure, not ML research. While the project has clearly assembled ML talent (Joel Lidin, others), Sam's journey into the world of blockchain, from nightclub promoter to DeFi CTO, represents a significant domain pivot. The team appears small (hiring for experienced ML researchers), and scaling from a research proof-of-concept to production training services requires enterprise engineering, sales, and support capabilities that the team has not yet demonstrated. The claim of prior co-founding Khalani is not independently verifiable — Tracxn lists Kevin Wang and Tannr Allard as founders.\n\n### Token/Dilution Risk\n\nThe current alpha token has extremely thin liquidity. The subnet is in a 100% burn period with no emissions being distributed. Plans for a separate Covenant token are mentioned but undefined, creating uncertainty about future tokenomics. If a new token is launched, the relationship between γ (Templar alpha), any new Covenant token, and TAO would need careful design to avoid diluting early supporters. Additionally, Bittensor's own halving mechanics mean that emission rewards will decrease over time, potentially reducing miner incentives before product revenue materializes.\n\n### Market Sizing Reality Check\n\nThe stated ambition is to "commoditize intelligence" and "commoditize decentralized learning." The total addressable market for AI training infrastructure is enormous — cloud GPU market alone is estimated at $80B+ by 2027. However, the realistic serviceable market for Covenant is significantly smaller: organizations willing to trade training control and speed for lower cost and decentralization. This likely starts as a niche: privacy-sensitive training, censorship-resistant model development, and community-owned AI. The path from niche to mainstream requires the performance gap to close substantially from the current ~60% of SOTA.\n\n---\n\n## Investment Considerations\n\n### Bull Case\n\n- **Technical moat is real and proven:** Covenant72B is the only fully permissionless, decentralized 72B model in existence. SparseLoCo and Gauntlet are peer-reviewed innovations accepted at NeurIPS. This isn't vaporware — it's working technology with a published arXiv report.\n\n- **Competitors are overfunded and underdelivering on decentralization:** Prime Intellect raised $20M promising decentralized AI training but trained its flagship model on a centralized 512-GPU cluster. Nous Research is actively building but has no timeline for when decentralized training will go live. Covenant is the only project that has actually done it.\n\n- **Massive upside from zero base:** With zero VC funding and no token sale, any investment enters at effectively pre-seed pricing. If decentralized training becomes viable at scale, Covenant's first-mover advantage and technical IP position it for enormous value creation.\n\n- **Crusades system creates a flywheel:** The MFU competition (already showing 66% up from 30%) means the community will continuously optimize training efficiency, creating a self-improving system that gets better over time without centralized R&D investment.\n\n- **Bittensor ecosystem tailwinds:** Bittensor has attracted serious institutional capital — Polychain ($200M), Digital Currency Group ($100M), Dao5 ($50M). Grayscale has filed for a Bittensor Trust. As the ecosystem matures, high-quality subnets like Templar could see disproportionate capital inflows.\n\n### Bear Case\n\n- **Performance gap may never close:** 60% of SOTA is a proof of concept, not a product. Centralized labs are advancing rapidly, and the gap could widen rather than narrow. Decentralized training has fundamental physics constraints (latency, synchronization) that may cap achievable model quality below commercially competitive levels.\n\n- **No revenue, no runway, no hiring capacity:** Without VC funding, Covenant cannot aggressively hire ML researchers, procure compute for R&D, or invest in enterprise sales infrastructure. Competitors with $50-70M+ will outpace them in talent acquisition and go-to-market execution.\n\n- **Bittensor ecosystem risk is systemic and non-trivial:** The entire project depends on a blockchain protocol that has experienced exploitation, governance controversies, and market manipulation. The dTAO mechanism is new and untested at scale. A major Bittensor failure would be catastrophic for Covenant.\n\n- **Team lacks ML depth compared to competitors:** Nous Research was founded by AI researchers; Prime Intellect has deep ML talent; Gensyn has research labs. Covenant was founded by blockchain engineers who pivoted to AI. The published research is promising but the team appears thin relative to the ambition.\n\n- **Enterprise market requires trust and credibility that decentralized systems struggle to provide:** Enterprises buying training services want SLAs, support contracts, data security guarantees, and compliance certifications. A permissionless system where anonymous miners train your model is fundamentally at odds with enterprise procurement requirements.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nCovenant AI represents one of the most technically authentic projects in the decentralized AI space. While competitors with $50-70M+ in funding have largely defaulted to centralized training for their flagship models, Covenant has actually delivered what the sector promises: a fully permissionless, globally distributed training run producing a 72B-parameter model with competitive benchmark results. The NeurIPS workshop acceptances and published arXiv report add unusual academic credibility for a Bittensor project. The Crusades MFU competition and Heterogeneous SparseLoCo research suggest a credible technical roadmap.\n\nHowever, the project faces a structural challenge: it is attempting to build a frontier AI training lab with zero external capital, a small team, and models that currently sit at ~60% of centralized SOTA. The transition from "technically impressive research proof-of-concept" to "commercially viable training infrastructure" is enormous and uncertain. The Bittensor dependency introduces additional systemic risk. The team's blockchain-first background, while a strength for protocol design, may be a limitation for the ML research depth required to close the performance gap.\n\n### Key Open Questions for Further Diligence\n\n1. **What specific enterprise clients are in the pipeline** for training/fine-tuning services, and what is the expected timeline and pricing?\n2. **What is the planned token architecture** for the unified Covenant token, and how will it relate to existing γ alpha tokens?\n3. **What is the team's plan for hiring ML researchers**, given the lack of traditional funding? Are there plans for a token sale or VC raise?\n4. **What are the specific benchmark targets** for the next training run (post-Crusades), and what model architecture/size is planned?\n5. **How will Basilica and Grail reach production readiness**, given they are still in development while the team is also iterating on Templar?\n\n### Key Metric to Watch\n\n**Crusades MFU progression** is the single most important near-term metric. If the competitive optimization system continues driving MFU higher (currently 66%, approaching centralized datacenter-level efficiency), it validates the core thesis that decentralized training can close the performance gap through crowdsourced optimization rather than centralized R&D spend. The second key metric is **time-to-revenue** from the planned training API services — the project must generate real demand before TAO emissions decline further through halving cycles.	complete	2026-03-13 08:57:25.047274
